<HEADLINE> Cyprus Hopes Recent Tension Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government favors a
speedy resolution of the prolonged Cyprus question, said an
official spokesman today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides Christofides said it is important
to note that the existing tension on the Mediterranean island
warrants a speedy settlement in Cyprus and efforts toward this
goal should be intensified.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot government shares the view of
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that tension in and around
Cyprus should be reduced to avoid a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday Annan expressed concern about
reports of increased tension between Greek and Turkish forces in
connection with military exercises in and around Cyprus and the
Eastern Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
A five-day Greek-Cypriot naval and air war game ended Tuesday
while Turkey responded with repeated violations of Cypriot and
Greek air space and a plan of military exercises in northern
Cyprus next month.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman urged Turkey to stop provocative actions against
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Christofides also stressed that "we have the right to carry
out army maneuvers and this is what we did in cooperation with
one of the guarantor powers, Greece, which has guaranteed our
independence and territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
Greece, Turkey and Britain were guarantors of Cyprus'
independence under the 1960 Treaty of establishment of the
Cyprus Republic.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have long been at
odds over a number of issues concerning the Aegean Sea as
well as Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece have maintained a joint defense pact,
signed in 1993, under which Greece would provide Cyprus with
military assistance in case the island is attacked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
