<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Get 800 Million Dollar Aid: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is expecting 800
million U.S. dollars of foreign aid from international donor
agencies in the next two months for its structural reform program,
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said here today.
</P>
<P>
After inaugurating a seminar on the country's 9th five-year
plan here, Sartaj told reporters that the foreign assistance is
expected to come from the World Bank, the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), the Asian Development Bank (ADB) and Japan.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the World Bank is scheduled to be held in the last
week of October to discuss and give its final approval to the
assistance of 250 million dollars for Pakistan's banking sector
reform program, Sartaj said.
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank will make the full disbursement once the loan
is approved at the board meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, Sartaj said that a meeting of the ADB Executive
Board will be held on November 6 in Manila to give final approval
to its 250 million dollars of assistance under a Capital Market
Development Program Loan (CMDPL).
A team comprising officials of the Finance Ministry and
representatives of the Stock Exchanges visited Manila last month
and successfully concluded negotiations with the ADB for the loan
to restructure the capital market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the finance minister said that Pakistan will also
get 300 million dollars as part of a 1.6-billion-dollar loan
package from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the IMF Executive Board will meet in
Washington on October 20 to approve the 1.6-billion-dollar loan
under the Extended Structural Adjustment Facility and the Extended
Fund Facility which provide cheap loans to Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
