<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Industrial Production Remains Strong in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Output at U.S. factories,
mines and utilities jumped by a strong 0.7 percent in September,
pushing the industrial operating rate to 84.4 percent of capacity,
the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The operating rate in last month was the highest since February
1995. But the strong increase normally would also be a warning
signal of a growing inflation pressure in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed said that much of the strength in industrial
production came from a 4.4 percent surge at utilities, pushing the
operating rate in the sector to 91.2 percent from 87.4 percent in
August.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing production increased by a moderate 0.4 percent
and raised the operating rate slightly to 83.4 percent from 83.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The increases in the production of light trucks, computers and
commercial aircraft and clothing offset drops in production of
consumer appliances and industrial machinery.
</P>
<P>
U.S. mining production fell 0.5 percent last month because of
declines at coal mines and oil and gas wells.
</P>
<P>
In advance, U.S. economists were expecting somewhat smaller
gains in both housing starts and industrial production. The
reports on new home construction and the industrial production
showed the U.S. economy expanded strongly in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
