<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, October 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cypriot government favors a speedy resolution of
the prolonged Cyprus question, said an official spokesman today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides Christofides said it is important
to note that the existing tension on the Mediterranean island
warrants a speedy settlement in Cyprus and efforts toward this
goal should be intensified.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot government shares the view of
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that tension in and around
Cyprus should be reduced to avoid a confrontation. (Cyprus-Tension)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Border soldiers of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) seized two South Korean farmers in the Demilitarized
Zone (DMZ) today.
</P>
<P>
Military sources in the DPRK were quoted by South Korea's
Yonhap news agency as saying that the farmers were caught because
they had earlier crossed the military demarcation line, the center
line of the four-km-wide buffer zone, into the north.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Defense Ministry reported earlier that the two
villagers were picking corn near the military demarcation line
just before noon when 12 DPRK troops crossed the demarcation line
and carried them into the north side. (DPRK-SKorean
Farmers-Seizure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of China's Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), said today that he received
a "very encouraging" response from Japanese leaders to building a
new partnership between Hong Kong and Japan
</P>
<P>
Tung made the remarks as he wrapped up his three-day visit to
Japan, his first trip to the country as HKSAR chief executive
following China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
the region on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Tung told a press conference before departure that he briefed
the Japanese leaders on the situation in Hong Kong after its
return, and had "very useful" exchanges of views on bilateral
ties, especially in trade and economy. (Tung-Japan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam and Iraq have signed a memorandum of
understanding on oil and gas cooperation, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed here by Vietnamese Deputy Prime
Minister Nguyen Cong Tan and his Iraqi counterpart Mohammed Al
Zubaidi on Thursday. The two sides also signed a rice deal, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi deputy prime minister's visit to Vietnam was
described by Vietnamese media as "a turning-point for further
expanding the ties between the two countries in the
future". (Vietnam-Iraq-Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said today that his
country has a stable system of political power based on the
Constitution and the situation is under his control.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address, he said a roundtable meeting
attended by the political parties would help solve the domestic
political crisis.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came two days after he reached a compromise with
Russia's lower house of the parliament, the State Duma, averting a
no-confidence vote in his government. (Russia-Politics) 
</P>
