<HEADLINE> Indian Agriculture Minister Asks to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian Agriculture Minister
Chaturanan Mishra today offered to step down in the face of
reported criticism of his ministry's performance by Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral, the Press Trust of India (PTI) said.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly-worded letter to Gujral, the Communist Party
leader said "the press is reporting that you are not satisfied
with my performance as minister.... Please allow me to go and ask
my party to replace me by someone more capable."
</P>
<P>
"If you were not satisfied, you should have told me of this
instead of speaking through the press," the minister was quoted as
saying in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Prime Minister Gujral had expressed concern
over poor spending of budgeted resources by some of the
ministries, including the Agriculture Ministry, while reviewing
the first quarter (from April to June) performance of various
government departments.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters later today, however, Mishra disclosed
that the prime minister, who is visiting Punjab, had spoken to him
over phone.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that he had never criticized Mishra's
functioning and considered him one of the best ministers, Mishra
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
