<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Offers to Open Financial Services Less Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of new or revised
offers to open financial services to foreign competition tabled at
talks ending today has been less than expected, a WTO official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
However, speaking at a briefing after the ending of a meeting
of the Committee on Trade in Financial Services of the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Committee Chairman Yoshio Okubo told
reporters, "I'm not discouraged by the limited number of offers as
of today, because more than a dozen delegations have expressed
their willingness to table their offers in a few weeks or as soon
as possible."
</P>
<P>
Okubo believed that negotiations meant to make a global pact to
free trade in financial services are on the track but time is
limited.
</P>
<P>
It has been the fifth meeting since the current negotiations
resumed in April. The tabling of the offers is a very important
aspect of the negotiations. Up to now, 24 offers have been
received from 38 participants, counting the European Community
(EC) as 15, and they are conditional and subject to the overall
outcome of the negotiations scheduled to end on December 12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Further meetings of the committee are planned in November with
a final meeting scheduled for December 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
