<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Host World Ecotourism Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is to host an
international ecotourism conference in a bid to popularize it in
Africa in the next millennium, Kenya Wildlife Service (KWS)
officials said today.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the first-ever workshop of this kind in
eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The conference, whose theme is called "Ecotourism -- Charting
the Way Forward," will focus on the relationship of ecotourism to
conservation, to local communities, and ultimately, to long-term
economic growth and sustainable development, said KWS officials.
</P>
<P>
The theory and practice of ecotourism, as well as global and
regional case studies on successful ecotourism models are also
expected to be discussed at the meeting, scheduled for October 27
to November 3.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the conference will be an exhibition of
community-based tourism activities, showcasing the unique
heritage, handicrafts and tourism development efforts of Kenya's
40-plus diverse cultures.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 delegates from the U.S., Britain, South Africa,
Mexico, Brazil, Belize, Tanzania, Swaziland, Uganda, Australia,
Botswana, Namibia, Mozambique, Malawi, Zimbabwe and other
countries will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ecotourism, defined as "responsible travel to natural areas
that conserves the environment and sustains the well-being of
local people," was popularized in Latin America first and became
a well-known idea during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
At the root of the ecotourism experience is the long history
of nature tourism which has flourished in the national parks of
the Untied States for over 100 years and in Kenya since the
1970s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
