<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Monument to Be Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Washington Monument, the
towering landmark on the skyline of the United States' capital,
will soon undergo repairs.
</P>
<P>
Target discount stores are leading a private corporate effort
to pay the five-million-dollar bill for the most extensive
overhaul of the monument since it opened to the public in 1888,
The Washington Post said.
</P>
<P>
Though the monument will close for up to four months early next
year for elevator and climate control repairs, it will remain open
for exterior work that will go on at least until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Target, a division of retailer Dayton Hudson Corp. based in
Minneapolis, is putting up the first one million dollars and
rounding up other donors to pay the rest of the bill.
</P>
<P>
General Electric is developing a lighting system for night
illumination of scaffolding designed by architect Michael Graves.
The scaffolding and a transparent covering, to be erected next
June, is designed to blend in with the monument's exterior while
allowing observers to see the memorial beneath the steel network.
</P>
<P>
The corporate involvement in restoring a national monument is
part of a growing trend in tight-money times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
