<HEADLINE> GCC Seeks Japanese Funds to Diversify Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) states have identified more than 100 industrial projects
they intend to present to Japanese investors as part of a drive to
diversify the oil-reliant Gulf economies.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 400 officials and businessmen from the six GCC
countries and their main economic trade partner Japan will gather
in Bahrain next month to discuss joint industrial ventures and
trade, the United Arab Emirates (UAE)'s Wam news agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The GCC has prepared a list of more than 100 feasible
industrial projects, mainly on light and medium products, to be
put forward to the Japanese side, according to Wam.
</P>
<P>
The November 23-26 conference in Bahrain will be held under
the theme "towards the establishment of permanent common
interests."
</P>
<P>
It is the nearest in the future in a series of meetings between
the two sides aimed at strengthening economic links and increasing
Japan's exports to the GCC countries, one of the major consumer
markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
Japan is GCC's top trade partner with two-way exchanges
standing at 36 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, nearly one third of
the alliance's total trade volume.
</P>
<P>
Japan also receives more than 70 percent of its oil needs from
the region and is increasingly reliant on Gulf liquefied natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
The GCC countries have pumped nearly 55 billion U.S. dollars
into more than 5,000 industrial projects in a drive to ease
dependence on oil earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
