<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lopez: No Imminent Clash Exist Between Greece, Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Admiral Joseph Lopez,
Commander-in-Chief of allied forces in southern Europe, today
ruled out the possibility that a serious incident between Greece
and Turkey will happen in the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in the northern Greek port city
of Thessaloniki after completion of the evaluation of the recent
NATO exercise "Dynamic Mix '97", Lopez said that the information
and indications he had received so far did not lead him to the
conclusion that a serious incident was imminent in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that NATO was doing everything possible to
secure cooperation and prevent clashes in the region.
</P>
<P>
"we are cooperating with diplomatic, economic and political
organizations and we support political solutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the harassment this week of the aircraft carrying
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos by Turkish warplanes,
both on his way and returning from Cyprus, Lopez stressed the
importance of dialogue, saying that "dialogue and cooperation are
helpful, regardless of whether they are conducted at a political or
military level."
</P>
<P>
As for NATO's new role following the political changes in
recent years, he said that the enemy was instability and the aim
of the alliance was to consolidate peace and stability through
dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have long been at odds
over a number of issues regarding the Aegean Sea as well as
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Tension between the two neighbors has in recent months been
intensified following the fruitless New York talks between the two
countries' foreign ministers, military exercises by Greece and
Cyprus and the repeated violations of Greek and Cypriot air space
by Turkish warplanes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Drug Sales Increase Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- US drug sales in the year to
August 1997 rose to 65 billion US dollars, 14 percent up on the
same period last year and almost four time as fast as those in
Europe, the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report by specialist pharmaceuticals market
researchers IMS International, the newspaper said that the sharp
increase in US sales so far this year is set to continue.
</P>
<P>
However, by contrast, drug sales in the seven biggest European
markets rose only four percent to 54.3 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that drug growth varied widely in Europe,
with UK and Spain growing the fastest, both rising eight percent
to 7.4 billion US dollars and 4.9 billion respectively. Italy
comes next, where sales rose seven percent to 8.8 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the slowest growing market in Europe, with sales
inching up one percent to 15 billion US dollars. Then comes
France, with sales growing two percent to 14.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
By medical area, the strongest growth was in nervous system
drugs, where sales rose 13 percent to 23.1 billion dollars while
heart drug sales grew six percent to 33.9 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Reduction Experts Pass Action Plan for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Experts passed an Action Plan
for disaster reduction activities over the next two years to be
implemented by a broad coalition including the United Nations,
governments, non-governmental organizations and the private sector
after a week-long meeting ending here today.
</P>
<P>
The ninth session of the Scientific and Technical Committee
(STC) of the International Decade for Natural Disaster Reduction
(IDNDR) was held here on October 13-17. The STC is an advisory
body of 25 experts around the world, appointed by the United
Nations Secretary-General, to provide scientific and technical
advice on disaster reduction issues.
</P>
<P>
In its final statement, the STC reaffirmed "the need for all
governments around the world to integrate disaster reduction and
risk management as an essential element of their development
planning and sustainable development policies". "It is of
paramount importance to ensure that there is a concerted and
coordinated international approach to risk reduction strategies in
the 21st century," it added.
</P>
<P>
"There will otherwise be no international foundation for risk
reduction strategies at the closing of the International Decade
for Natural Disaster Reduction (1990-2000). A new approach to
disaster reduction, on the basis of an evaluation of the IDNDR's
achievements, must be collectively agreed to by the international
community", the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The IDNDR plan of activities for the next two years is based on
five primary themes: hazards, vulnerability and risk assessment;
early warning issues; disasters and sustainable development;
political and public policy commitment; shared knowledge and
technology transfer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
