<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nyerere Advocates Economic Solidarity Of African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the South
Commission, Julius Nyerere, has reiterated his call for economic
solidarity among African countries, especially those in the
sub-Sahara region to enhance their capacity for development.
</P>
<P>
If Africans do help each other, no one else would come to
their rescue because the interest of Africa is not in the
interest of the main power blocs in the world, said Nyerere today
in Johannesburg, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
He said sub-Sahara Africa has been isolated because it is not
in the orbit of any of the power blocs of the rich north.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he noted, while the US might be afraid of
unemployment in Mexico and would devise strategies to deal with
it and while Europe might similarly fear north African
unemployment, they have no similar reasons for fearing
unemployment in sub-Saharan Africa because it is isolated from
them.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, "we in sub-Saharan Africa can easily be
forgotten," said the former president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he called on African countries to rethink about
themselves and work together for the benefit of all their people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking particularly on South Africa, which is regarded as an
economic "big brother" of Africa, Nyerere said South Africa
should work out not only for its own benefit, but also for the
benefit of all Africa.
</P>
<P>
"You have to prosper together with neighbors, because if you
decide to go it alone, you will be overwhelmed by the poverty of
your neighbors," the seasoned statesman said.
</P>
<P>
On the latest developments in Africa, Nyerere stressed the
need for democratic practices in all countries, and cautioned the
governments not to behave like sponges that soak everything which
come to their way.
</P>
<P>
"The era of the Mobutus or Mobutuism is gone," he said.
"Africa needs properly elected governments which are responsive
to the needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere who arrived in Johannesburg on Wednesday is expected
to introduce his recently formed Mwalimu Nyerere Foundation to
South African opinion makers and businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
