<HEADLINE> Bre-X Shareholders Sue for Three Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Shareholders of Bre-X Minerals
Ltd. has sued its directors, financial advisers and engineering
consultants for three billion dollars (2.1 billion USD), a report
said today.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit came less than 24 hours after a judge in the
Canadian province of Alberta paved the way for derivative actions.
</P>
<P>
Derivative suits rob defendants of one powerful potential
defense argument that their duty was to the firm, not to the
shareholders directly.
</P>
<P>
The latest suit is filed in the name of the Calgary,
Alberta-based exploration firm, the Financial Post newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
The suit, filed Thursday in Ontario Court, names SNC-Lavalin
Inc. and its Kilborn Engineering subsidiaries, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
Inc., Republic National Bank of New York as well as Bre-X officers
and directors.
</P>
<P>
"The conduct of the insiders...was high-handed, outrageous,
reckless, wanton, entirely without care, deliberate, callous,
disgraceful, willful...and motivated by economic considerations,"
the statement of claim said.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street powerhouse J.P. Morgan and Republic National Bank
"should have known the plaintiff was relying in part on the due
diligence investigations conducted by the financial advisers," the
statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The suit is the latest of several class action lawsuits filed
for investors who lost heavily when the Indonesian gold find
turned out to be a hoax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
