<HEADLINE> Hydro-Electricity Eases Power Shortness in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Deputy Prime
Minister Kassu Ilala said today that the pressing demand for
energy supply in the country would be mitigated with the entry into
service of hydroelectric power stations in the coming five and
six years.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at a trade fair and bazaar here, Kassu said
efforts are being made to generate an additional power of 700 mega
watt which will help supply power to the industry sector at a
relatively low price.
</P>
<P>
He said, the plan to install an additional 600,000 telephone
lines in a bid to raise access to communication facilities.
</P>
<P>
The service of mobile telephone will start in a few months
time, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the sub-sector of the metal engineering industry which
could have a great bearing on the overall development is now
receiving the necessary support following the establishment of an
independent agency responsible for its revitalization.
</P>
<P>
On the training institutes to be set up in the country, Kassu
said a new tanning and leather products industry training institute
would begin operation next year while a textile technology
training program has already been launched this year.
</P>
<P>
He added that four additional engineering faculties which
could train students at degree level are being set up bring the
total number of such faculties to five.
</P>
