<HEADLINE> UK Planned Super-SIB Will Not Work, Warns Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 17 (Xinhua) - Britain's plans to roll nine
different financial regulators into a single organization will not
work, an expert on the subject warned.
</P>
<P>
Michael Taylor, a reader in financial regulation at the
University of Reading, said in his book entitled Will Super-SIB
Work? The planned organization will have to take on so many tasks
that it will be unable to operate effectively.
</P>
<P>
Super-SIB will suffer from "management overstretch from an
impossibly broad range of responsibilities, from conflicting
cultures, from a lack of accountability and oversight", he warned.
</P>
<P>
It was announced earlier that the new organization plans a
ceremonial launch on October 20.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, a former Bank of England official, said the case for a
single regulator for the entire financial services sector has
"triumphed by default and the policy issues it raises have not
begun to be addressed".
</P>
<P>
He argued that it was very difficult for one regulator to
pursue conflicting goals such as the stability of the financial
system, the protection of consumers and the preservation of
orderly markets.
</P>
<P>
Taylor's proposal is for separate commissions, charged
respectively with financial stability, consumer protection and
market integrity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
