<HEADLINE> Regional Meeting Discusses Cross-Border Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The fourth east African
technical working groups meeting on common border initiative
opened in Masaka, southwestern Uganda today, reported Radio
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, the Ugandan State Minister for Foreign
Affairs in charge of regional cooperation, Rebecca Kadaga, said
that the Ugandan government has been able to dismantle the
barriers to the cross border flow of foods, persons and capital.
</P>
<P>
She ensured the delegates that the government will continue
diversifying itself from business and create more opportunities
for the private sector and also create confidence in private
sector's useful partners in the economic development of three
east African countries.
</P>
<P>
She noted that some aspects of cross border initiatives are
costly for some governments which need a lot of revenue,
employment and heavy competition for infant industries.
</P>
<P>
Kadaga hoped that the technical working groups will continue
providing technical support for the project implementation
committees in their respective communities.
</P>
<P>
The consultant of regional economic integration project, Sam
Katabazi, said that the objective of the meeting is to harmonize
and review what has been done and achieved by member states of
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) since
1992.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, founded in December 1994, is to integrate the member
states economy by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
