<HEADLINE> Canadian Firms Not Train Staff Enough, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada risks a slip in its
competitiveness in the knowledge-based global economy if its
companies don't train their employees, according to the latest
report from an economic think-tank here.
</P>
<P>
Currently, less than one-third of Canadian firms do any
training at all, says the report, which was prepared by the
Conference Board of Canada.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, about 74 percent of employees in Japan and 80
percent in Britain receive on the job training.
</P>
<P>
"Canadian industry, generally, is underinvesting in the
development of its human resources," the report says.
</P>
<P>
Most Canadian firms minimize labor costs to stay competitive,
which means the workers don't learn the skills that would make
them more productive, notes the report.
</P>
<P>
The status quo is worrisome, since research shows
employer-based training produces a 30 percent rate of return
compared with just 10 percent from formal higher education, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll of workers in 49 countries by the World Economic
Forum found Canadian rate their workplace worse than those of
other nations for in-company training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Cuts Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's central bank,
the Reserve Bank, has decided to cut its lending rates by one
percentage point to 16 percent with effect from next Monday, South
African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the financial aggregates used by the Reserve Bank as a
basis for monetary policy decisions have moved in the right direction
recently to justify a reduction in the bank rate," Reserve Bank
governor Chris Stals said today.
</P>
<P>
Stals said that while certain statistics, such as money supply,
remained above the bank's guidelines, recent declines were
nevertheless encouraging.
</P>
<P>
The money supply increased by an annualized 13.9 percent in
August, down from 15.9 percent in April this year, but was still above
Stals' target of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Credit extended to the private sector had fallen from over 17
percent in April to a relatively high 14.6 percent in August, but the
three month seasonally adjusted average to August had declined to a
low of 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Stals said he was encouraged by the turnaround since early this
year in the trend for consumer and producer inflation.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index peaked at 9.9 percent in April before
falling to 8.7 percent in August, while the producer price index has
dropped to 5.9 percent from a high of 9.6 percent in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Other positive trends were the stabilization of the exchange rate
since the sharp depreciation of 21.9 percent last year, and the jump
in gross reserves from only 10.3 billion Rand (2.2 billion U.S.
Dollars) at the end of last year to the current 26.5 billion (5.6
billion dollars ).
</P>
<P>
"South Africa has successfully weathered the storms of last year in
the foreign exchange market and has, to an important extent, succeeded
in preventing an escalation in the adverse effects of the depreciation
on domestic financial conditions," Stals said.
</P>
<P>
The progress made in establishing greater financial
stability should contribute to job creation, he added.
</P>
<P>
South African commercial banks can be expected to follow the
Reserve Bank's lead and reduce their prime lending rates in the near
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
