<HEADLINE> Governments Urged to Fund Public Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Donors and governments
are suggested here today to increase funding for public health
services and research to bring a healthier world into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the Eighth International Public Health Congress
ended in Arusha, in north Tanzania made the appeal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The congress, which was held for the first time in Africa in the
30-year history of World Federation of Public Health Association
(WFPHA), and the second time in a developing country, will hold its
next meeting in China in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The 600-plus delegates from 55 countries agreed that in
transition to the 21st century, health promotion will be an
essential tool for human development.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day congress, delegates also took up the AIDS
issue, saying that concerted efforts are needed to control the
virus, which is killing millions of people in the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts, non-governmental organizations, donors and
academicians have urged the ban of smoking in public places, such
as trains and airlines.
</P>
<P>
They also condemned the growth of tobacco exports from west
to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In order to regulate medical practices, the delegats called on the
governments to coordinate in public and private services.
</P>
</TEXT>
