<HEADLINE> China Trying to Win Africa's Aircraft Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese aircraft manufacturers made
flying demonstrations today at an air force base in Zambia's capital in
a bid to market their aviation products.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations, which is co-sponsored by China Aviation Industry
Corporation and China Aviation Technology Import and Export
Corporation, attracted several hundred people including Chitalu Sampa,
Minister of Home Affairs, R. Shikapwashya,
Air Force Commander and Wang Yunxiang, Chinese Ambassador to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Chinese aircraft manufacturers have focused their attention in
recently years on the African market where the Chinese-made aviation
products are more popular because of their good quality and low
prices, He Fukang, deputy managing director of the Nanchang-based
company told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations are aimed to make more and more potential
African buyers to know about China's advanced aeronautical
technologies and expand China's market shares,
said He.
</P>
<P>
During the two-hour demonstrations, one delicately designed K-8 jet
trainer, which is made by Nanchang Aircraft Manufacturing Company and
whose speed varies from 180 kilometers to 800 kilometers per hour,
made dazzling exhibition and aroused bursts of warm applause from the
viewers.
</P>
<P>
The other two aircraft, one Y-7 100 airliner for feeder lines and
one Y7H-500 transport plane also made wonderful demonstrations to show
their excellent functions compared with their low prices.
</P>
<P>
Both of them are made by Xi'an Aircraft Industry Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese flying demonstration was first made earlier this week
in Zimbabwe and will continue in Kenya and Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
