<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rival Kurds Agree to Stop Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Feuding Kurdish factions
have agreed to stop fighting, which has last several days in
northern Iraq, under the mediation of Western countries, the State
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) and the Kurdistan
Democratic Party (KDP) declared the cease-fire at 20:00 hours
local (1700 GMT) and the United States, Turkey and Britain, who
jointly sponsored a peace process among the Kurds, called upon the
two Kurdish factions to observe the cease-fire, the State
Department said.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between the two groups broke out a week ago and PUK
forces were reported to have hit the KDP headquarters in the town
of Sararush.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said the three countries co-sponsoring the
so-called Ankara peace process had established that the cease-fire
violations came from PUK-controlled territory. They called on the
PUK to withdraw to positions they held before October 12.
</P>
<P>
"We were involved very intensively the past three days to try
to walk the parties back and observe a cease-fire," State
Department spokesman James Foley said. "This finally bore fruit
today." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
