<HEADLINE> Northern Iraqi Kurdish Parties Urged to Respect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey, the United States
and Britain today called on two warring northern Iraqi parties
to respect cease-fire and immediately stop their fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a written statement that
the three sponsors of the two-year-old Ankara process urged the
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) to withdraw their troops from the conflicting
areas.
</P>
<P>
"The three countries hold that any fighting in this area is
unacceptable," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian PUK and the KDP, allegedly backed by Turkey
and Iraq, have been fighting each other for the control of
northern Iraq following the 1990 Gulf War. Over the past several
days, clashes between them intensified in the region.
</P>
<P>
The statement also quoted the Peace Monitoring Force (PMF) as
confirmed that it was the PUK that provoked the clashes,
demanding an immediate cease-fire for the resumption of PMF
operation.
</P>
<P>
The first PMF group, comprising 180 Iraqi Turkmens and 20
Assyrians, was deployed in northern Iraq last April to supervise
the truce reached between PUK and KDP earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara process, designed to end the armed conflicts in
northern Iraq, had hold three rounds of peace talks in the
Turkish capital since early last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
