<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Debt Jumps in Slovak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign debt in the Republic of
Slovak increased by about 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in the first
half of this year, the Slovak National Bank said recently.
</P>
<P>
Pavol Kyjac, a senior official of the bank, said that by the
end of June 1997, Slovak's total foreign debt stood at 9.03
billion U.S. dollars, a 203 percent jump since 1993 when the
country became independent.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, foreign debt per capita rose from 562
dollars to 1,750 dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Slovak's current foreign debt accounts for 42.5 percent of the
country's total gross domestic product (GDP). 
</P>
</TEXT>
