<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Xijiang River Blocked For Shipping Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Xijiang River, a major
tributary of China's third largest river, the Zhujiang, was
blocked this evening for construction work on the Guigang
Navigation Hub.
</P>
<P>
The work was difficult because of the velocity of the river and
an enormous water flow, but was done one month ahead of schedule
in November. Engineers hope to have one more dry month for
construction.
</P>
<P>
The project began in November 1994 and has cost two billion
yuan, including 80 million US dollars in World Bank loans, for
construction, clearing the project area and the channel, and
setting up a transportation network.
</P>
<P>
It is the second phase of the Xijiang Project, which was
approved by the central government in 1981, for clearing the 854
km-waterway between Nanning, the capital of the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, and Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong
province, and is part of a government plan for a large
transportation network of waterways, railways and highways.
</P>
<P>
The Guigang Navigation Hub consists of a dam, shiplocks, and
generators with a total capacity of 120,000 kw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
