<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU not to Give up its Role in Mideast: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) would not
give up its role in the Mideast peace process and the role was not
subject to reconsideration, EU special envoy to the Middle East
Miguel Angel Moratinos was quoted today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The EU defends its interests in the region with the spirit of
partnership and solidarity and "we create more favorable
political and economic environment and brighter prospects for the
relations between Europe and its neighbors," local daily
Assabah today quoted Moratinos as saying.
</P>
<P>
The commitment of the concerned parties in the Middle East
peace process is unrevocable, said the EU official who arrived
here early this week to exchange views with Tunisian leaders on
ways of reviving the peace process stalemated by the
uncompromising policy of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli government led by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is clearly concentrating on the security aspects, he
said, adding that the concerned parties have to give higher
priority to defusing the tension in the security area.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos urged for the adoption of new approach to security
that is more realistic and viable and depends on the fact that the
more progress is made in the peace process the more security is
attained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he denied that the recent difficulties in the peace
process have weakened the position of Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, Arafat is still an active element in the
Palestinian society and he is the only one who can okay a final
accord with Israel," Moratinos said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
