<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK To Promote Business Ties with Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC) will hold a series of activities to
promote business ties between Hong Kong and Europe during Chief
Executive Tung Chee-hwa's visit to Europe on October 19-23.
</P>
<P>
A highlight of the European mission will be the inauguration of
the Hong Kong/European Union and European Union/Hong Kong Business
Cooperation Committees, a bilateral initiative spearheaded by the
TDC.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee-hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China, will deliver an opening
address at the first plenary session of the committees, to be held
on October 20 in Brussels, the first leg of Tung's European tour.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Committee is chaired by TDC Chairman Victor
Fung. The EU Committee is chaired by Chairman of Godman Sachs
International Peter Sutherland, who is former director-general of
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). Committee
members are all corporate leaders of the most important
manufacturing and service industries from both regions.
</P>
<P>
The Brussels mission will see the launch of another important
TDC initiative -- the TDC Annual Dinner in Europe. Each year it
will bring top policy makers, opinion formers and business leaders
together from across Europe to hear about latest developments in
Hong Kong and opportunities for closer business ties.
</P>
<P>
The TDC's long-established Annual Dinner in London will be held
on October 21. British government leaders will be among the 400
guests. London is the second leg of Tung's European tour.
</P>
<P>
The London Dinner, one of the TDC's most successful channels
for high-level networking, plays a particular important role in
strengthening links between the financial services sectors of Hong
Kong and the city of London.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union is Hong Kong's third largest trading
partner. Expanding the partnership with Europe is very important
to our role as Asia's hub for international business," said TDC
Chairman Victor Fung.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
