<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Tightened in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine police authorities,
alarmed by Tuesday's terrorist attack on a military camp, decided
to seal off the southern provinces of Sulu and Tawi-Tawi to
prevent undocumented foreigners from entering the country.
</P>
<P>
Chief Superintendent Franco Calida, police director of the
Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM), issued the order to
isolate the two provinces, seen as the country's backdoor, the
Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Calida said the move is aimed to prevent a repeat of Tuesday's
suicide attack on Camp Siongco, the Army's Sixth Infantry Division
headquarters, located in Sinsuat town, Maguindanao province in
central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
During the attack, two suspected Muslim extremists, one
Pakistani and one Saudi Arabian, entered Camp Siongco, and shot
dead three soldiers before they themselves were killed.
</P>
<P>
The two attackers were accompanied by two Filipino companions
who acted as lookouts at the gate and escaped.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Calida also enforced a local authentication process
for foreigners to determine the legality of their stay in the two
isolated island provinces.
</P>
<P>
Calida explained that the process is not aimed at "harassing"
foreigners but to know the purpose of their stay in the country.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners who do not have appropriate travel documents will be
handed over to the Bureau of Immigration and Deportation.
</P>
<P>
Most foreigners present in Tawi-Tawi and Sulu are reportedly
Pakistani and Egyptian missionaries teaching Islam to local
residents.
</P>
<P>
Both the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) and Abu Sayyaf,
the country's two remaining Muslim rebel groups, have strongly
denied involvement in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The main rebel faction, the Moro National Liberation Front,
signed a peace accord with the government last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
