<HEADLINE> Chen Yan Strikes Fourth Swimming Gold at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yan, who has broken two
world records and reapt three golds in the swimming pool, won her
fourth title in the women's 800 meters freestyle at the Eighth
National Games here Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Chen clocked an Asian record-breaking time of eight minutes
27.94 seconds for the gold, followed by Chen Hua of Zhejiang
province in 8:32.11 and Jiangxi's Luo Ping in 8:36.19.
</P>
<P>
Chen also anchored her Liaoning teammates for a silver in the
women's 4X200m freestyle relay. But the medal was disqualified
later because of a start fault.
</P>
<P>
The relay event was won by the local foursome in 7:58.60.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old teenage sensation failed to qualify for the
finals of the 200m backstroke after finishing last in her group in
heats this morning.
</P>
<P>
"I had to give up one of the two events," she said. "Or I will
lose both."
</P>
<P>
The relay was the last event the Liaoning star competed in the
National Games, which will end its swimming competition on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to win four gold medals at the Games," Chen
said. "After all, it is held only every four years."
</P>
<P>
With the most glittering feat at the Games, the teenager now
sets her sights upon the World Swimming Championships slated next
January in Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best to achieve good results there," she said.
"I will resume training as soon as possible after the Games."
</P>
<P>
But jumping to stardom at an early age of 16, she inevitably
raised concerns that she might meet more pressures in mind in the
future international competitions.
</P>
<P>
"Pressure? Yes, it is unavoidable. But I'll try not to think
about it," she said.
</P>
<P>
Zhen Yinjuan, gold medalist in the women's 100m backstroke,
proved her status as a backstroke queen by grabbing the 200m gold
in 2:08.51.
</P>
<P>
"It is just a beginning, I hope I can do better in the Swimming
Worlds in Perth," the Guangdong native said.
</P>
<P>
"She has trained very hard in the past year for the Games," her
coach Wu Jinpei said. "She often spent extra time in training by
herself."
</P>
<P>
He Cihong of the Chinese Army, world record holder in the
women's 100m backstroke, was beaten into second place in 2:10.21,
0.50 seconds ahead of third placer Wu Yanyan of Guangxi, who set a
world record in the women's 200m individual medley on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 50m freestyle, local hero Jiang Chengji, who
finished a record fourth place in the Atlanta Olympic Games,
captured the title in 22.54 seconds, the fifth gold he won in the
National Games.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200m individual medley gold went to Shanghai's Wang
Wei, who touched home first with a new Asian record of 2:02.36.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
