<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Undecided on Whether to Go to Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid said here today that the league has yet
to decide if it will take part in the fourth Middle East and North
Africa economic conference slated for November 16-18 in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League has not yet determined its stance. Contacts
are still under way in this respect," the AL chief said before
heading for Beirut to attend the 7th conference of Arab
businessmen and investors, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The 22-member Arab League has received an invitation from the
host Qatar. But it conditioned its participate on progress in the
Mideast peace process, putting pressure on Israel to change its
hardline policies.
</P>
<P>
The peace process came to a halt in March after Israel
obstinately went ahead with the building of a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem despite world outcry.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries have either rejected or threatened to
boycott the Doha conference which is to include Israel. But Qatar
said it expects 82 countries, including 12 Arab countries, at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdul-Meguid, the conference in Lebanon organized
by the AL and the Arab Institution for Investment Guarantees is
aimed at attracting investment funds to the Arab world and
encouraging Arab cooperation in economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
He said he will meet with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri, Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri and a number
of senior Arab officials in Beirut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mandela's Visit to Libya Evokes Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 18 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has been criticized by opposition parties and the
United States for his decision to visit Libya.
</P>
<P>
Announcing Mandela's tour this week, the Department of Foreign
Affairs of South Africa said Mandela would visit Libya and Egypt
en route to the Commonwealth summit in Edinburgh from October 24
to 27.
</P>
<P>
"Libya is a country which was very supportive of the South
African liberation struggle against apartheid, and is one of the
countries that the president has not visited since his
inauguration," the department said.
</P>
<P>
It said relations and bilateral trade between the two sides
have been on a sound footing since South Africa's democratic
elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
But the United States has expressed its "disapproval" of the
visit. State Department spokesman James Foley said his country
"believes" that diplomatic contacts with Libya "ought to be
maintained at a low level", and "we would be disappointed with a
visit of any head of state."
</P>
<P>
He said, according to U.N Security Council resolutions 748 and
883, flights into Tripoli, capital of Libya, are a violation of
sanctions, and that would be "a very special concern".
</P>
<P>
Responding to U.S. pressure, South African foreign affairs
spokesman Peter Swanepoel said Mandela would be travelling by
road to Tripoli and would not be violating U.N. sanctions against
Libya by flying to Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Nor would Mandela's visit affect relations with the United
States, which regards Libya as a sponsor of international
terrorism, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa's National Party spokesman Boy
Geldenhuys said Mandela should cancel his visit to Libya as it
would cause serious detrimental consequences for South Africa's
national interests.
</P>
<P>
Not only would the visit put South Africa on a collision
course with the international politics, it could also be damaging
to the country's relations with the United States, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
According to the opposition party's position, the U.S. is by
far the largest donor of development aid to South Africa, and if
that tap was turned off, the under-developed communities would be
the ones to suffer.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Democratic Party leader Tony Leon said
Mandela's decision was to "cock a snook" at world opinion.
</P>
<P>
"It does the ANC (African National Congress) no credit that
some of its main supporters during the years of apartheid were
pariah nations like Cuba and Libya, whose commitment to human
rights leaves much to be desired," claimed the opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
But the ANC has said it will continue to develop South
Africa's relations and cooperations with Libya and Cuba, as well
as Iran.
</P>
<P>
The foreign affairs spokesman also said that while South
Africa was well aware of the U.S. position, it also had bilateral
relations with Libya, a fellow member of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) and of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM).
</P>
<P>
The government did not believe that Mandela's visit to Libya
would affect South Africa's relations with the United States, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been embroiled in a row with Britain and the U.S.
over its refusal to extradite two suspects for the bombing of a
Pan-Am jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya, backed by the OAU and NAM, has suggested a compromise,
calling for the trial to be held in a neutral country, by
Scottish judges under Scottish law. The matter is now before the
International Court.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Mandela will try to broker some sort of
resolution to this matter during his visit to Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Garment Fair in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Clothing factories from
across China and from several other countries have come for a
six-day international garment fair that opened today in Humen
Town, Dongguan City, South China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the town's second and China's fourth largest, after
the Dalian, Beijing, and Shanghai fairs. It is sponsored by the
China Garment Association, the Chinese Garment Industry
Corporation and the local government.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 international name-brand garments are being traded
at the fair, where international fashion trends for fall and
winter collections will be announced. There will also be a series
of other events like clothing design contests, fashion shows, and
an evening party.
</P>
<P>
Trading this time is expected to increase considerably from the
1.3 billion yuan at the first fair in 1996.
</P>
<P>
With 500 big clothing factories and 8,000 garment shops, Humen
produces more than 60 million items of clothing a year and had
a clothing turnover of over 6.6 billion yuan in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0085 </DOCNO>
