<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Maintain Current Export Duty of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of
Industry, Trade and Tourism Oldemiro Baloi announced here on
Friday that the government will keep the 14 percent export duty
of raw cashew nut unchanged for at least the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government made the decision after considering
a study on Mozambique's cashew nut production and procession by
an international consultancy, views and suggestions from the
cashew nut industry, the World Bank and other organizations,
local paper "Noticias" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The export duty of cashew nut should be paid on the export day
by exporters, according to the government decision.
</P>
<P>
A cashew association will also be set up to replace the
Secretariat of State for Cashew Nut and it will be given more
power to intervene cashew nut production, procession and export.
</P>
<P>
The output of cashew nuts in Mozambique was once on the top in
the world, with the highest record of 220,000 tons. But it only
produced 60,000 tons of cashew nuts last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
