<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Bacteria Found in S. African River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Alarm has rung for local
residents when tests showed that the Klip River bordering South
Africa's Free State and Mpumalanga provinces was contaminated
with cholera-causing bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Results of the tests revealed on Friday showed that the water
samples contained two infective cholera-causing sub-species,
local meidia reported.
</P>
<P>
Health experts said that owing to the presence of the two
sub-species, there is a 99 percent chance that some people would
become carriers of the intestinal disease and others may become
sick and die.
</P>
<P>
Cholera is a bacterial disease, spread mainly through
contaminated water, that causes severe diarrhea and vomiting and
rapid dehydration. Patients can recover within 24 hours if
treated immediately after diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng's Health department was alerting hospitals and clinics
to test all patients with severe diarrhea for cholera from
Friday, and were hurriedly putting together brochures for an
information campaign to prevent the potentially fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
They have been expecting the arrival of cholera in South
Africa since the disease broke out in Mozambique about a month
ago. The government in Kenya, where a cholera outbreak killed 140
people this year, has appealed to the World Health Organization
for help.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,500 people have been taken to hospital since
cholera first broke out in that country eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's drinking water supplier, Rand Water, has
launched a massive education campaign aimed at preventing a
possible outbreak of cholera in the contaminated area. Leaflets
were delivered to schools, clinics and shops.
</P>
<P>
Rand Water warned residents along the Klip River to avoid
contact with the river water and watch for early symptoms of
cholera.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in the area have been told to treat every case of
diarrhea as a possible cholera case.
</P>
<P>
The contamination of the Klip River reportedly stems from
sewerage and industrial effluent discharged in rivers.
</P>
<P>
Water Affairs spokesman Marius Keet said his department was
working on pinpointing the culprits responsible for the
pollution, before forcing companies to clean up the river.
</P>
<P>
The results of the tests sparked a wave of panic among
residents along the Klip River. They are poised to sue Water
Affairs Minister Kader Asmal, unless his department forces
sewerage works to clean up the river immediately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
