<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Outbreak Kills Hundreds in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 18 (Xinhua) -- An outbreak of cholera has
killed hundreds of people in Nigeria in the last three months,
This Day newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the epidemic was first spotted in the north,
when it claimed unspecified number of residents in the Kano city,
including students at the Bayero University in Kano City.
</P>
<P>
Since then, it has forced the closure of the university and
appears to be spreading fast to other parts of the country, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to it, several slum areas in the Lagos State,
including Amukoko, Ajegunle and Alaba are worst hit by the
disease, as residents there have been supplied with reddish water
in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
It quoted state water corporation sources as saying that the
water supply pipe in the areas have been damaged during road
construction.
</P>
<P>
Health experts have blamed on the outbreak on unhygienic
environment, dirty preparation and handling of food and water,
and transmission through victims.
</P>
<P>
They called for the education of the public on the disease's
transmission and on how to keep good personal hygienic habits.
They also called for an earlier warning system and improved
immunization services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
