<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Demographers Say Community Important In Family Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese demographers are
suggesting that family planning work in China's rural areas should
be tied to rural community development for better results.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Peng Xizhe, director of Fudan University's Population
Research Institute, says that community-based rural development
has proven effective in getting farmers to be more enthusiastic
about family planning.
</P>
<P>
As the basic social unit of economic affairs and welfare
programs, the rural community, either a village or a town, may
strongly influence couples or individuals in the process of family
decision-making, he explains.
</P>
<P>
If a well-developed community can provide business
opportunities, and better cultural, health, and welfare services
for farmers, they will be more willing to accept family planning
policy, he says.
</P>
<P>
Peng's opinion is shared by his colleague, Prof. Dai Xingyi,
who took part in a research program titled "Network for Community
Based Development and Family Planning".
</P>
<P>
China's rural areas have more than 700 million people, and
have been vital to population-control efforts since the late
1970s. However, an under-developed economy and some deep-rooted
outdated concepts have remained major obstacles.
</P>
<P>
The government has recently called for integrating the rural
family planning program with economic development and farmer
assistance in business.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese rural residents are quite practical," says Prof. Li
Jingneng with Nankai University's Population Research
Institute. "If they are free of worries in their lives, health
care, and social welfare, they can be persuaded and do it on their
own."
</P>
<P>
"Although the community model is still at the experimental
stage, I think it is a very good direction and will be promising,"
Peng says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Lawmakers Examine Water Law's Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- A vice-chairman of the
Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress has urged
government to fight flooding and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
Wang Bingqian said that the work to control rivers, find water
resources and control flooding should be in concert with water and
soil conservation and water pollution control.
</P>
<P>
Wang made the remarks today in the capital of Hunan Province,
while inspecting the implementation of the Water Law there.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that water resource shortages, pollution, wasted
water resources, and flooding are still serious, even though there
have been some good results in conservation and protection of
water resources since the law went into effect in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Water resource departments should be more open-minded and
utilize foreign funds boldly and rationally, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The 13-day inspection was near Dongting Lake, China's second
largest, which is a crucial flood prevention and protection area
on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhenhuai, a member of the NPC Standing Committee and
co-chairman of the NPC Environmental and Resources Protection
Committee, urged Hunan's government to more conscientiously
implement the Water Law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
