<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, IMF At Odds on Loan Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has disagreed with the
International Monetary Fund's (IMF) request to reduce the
country's budget deficit in 1998 to zero and to contain wages rise
at 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between Muravei Radev, Bulgarian minister of
finance and the IMF representative over the past days on the loans
provided by the IMF to Bulgaria did not process smoothly, said a
press report.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and the IMF reached a series of agreements in March,
under which Bulgaria was provided with loans of 650 million
U.S. dollars, and in return would conform with some restrictions
imposed by the IMF on macroscopic economic indexes.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, which considered the terms raised by the IMF on the
deficit too harsh, only agreed to first slash the deficit to 25
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian government had planned to raise wages by 40
percent next year, as against 36 percent set by the IMF which
translates into an average monthly salary of 173,000 levs (about
100 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The IMF strictly reviewed Bulgaria's financial directorate
before each loan was granted. The loans actually granted so far
have accounted for less than one-third of the contract loans.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria registered its worst economic performance yet in 1996,
with a 9 percent drop in GDP, 311 percent inflation, and a 600
percent devaluation of the lev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
