<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tens of Thousands of Traffic Law Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 18 (Xinhua) -- South African traffic
authorities have achieved preliminary result since the start of
the Arrive Alive Campaign on October 1, local daily "Saturday
Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
In Gauteng Province alone, traffic officials have charged
135,640 drivers for offences ranging from failure to wear a
seatbelt to drunken driving, the report said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is administratively divided into nine provinces.
Gauteng Province has the worst road safety record in the country.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng Transport Department authorities said earlier that the
campaign would intensify and by the end of this month, mobile
courts would be in place at roadblocks to ensure that suspects
were dealt with swiftly.
</P>
<P>
"The local authorities are doing their best to ensure that
motorists will abide by the rules and law-abiding citizens will
finally feel safe on the roads," said a department spokesman Delc
Maluleke.
</P>
<P>
Traffic authorities in provinces of KwaZulu Natal and the
Western Cape, where the campaign is also under way, have reported
similar successes, and numerous road blocks have been held in
those provinces.
</P>
<P>
Traffic disorders, including reckless driving, drunk-driving
and exceeding the speed limit, have been one of serious social
problems in South Africa, which have cost the South African
economy close to 12 billion Rand (2.55 billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Arrive Alive Campaign will run until January and will be
focused on Gauteng, KwaZulu Natal and the Western Cape, where 76
percent of all accidents on South African roads occur. It is the
largest co-ordinated action taken against traffic offenders in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
