<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solidarity Union Veteran Named New Polish PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski Friday appointed Jerzy Buzek, a Solidarity Union
veteran and chemistry professor, as Poland's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Buzek, nominated earlier this week by Solidarity Election
Action (AWS) and its coalition partner, the Freedom Union (UW), is
expected to form a center-right cabinet in 14 days.
</P>
<P>
His appointment came after the resignation earlier Friday of
the the leftist government led by Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz, whose
Democratic Left Alliance (SLD) lost majority in the parliament in
the September 21 election.
</P>
<P>
Cimoszewicz's SLD, allied with the Peasant Party, has been in
power since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Though some successes have been achieved in economic reforms
over the past four years, the Polish public has become unsatisfied
with worsening social problems. The frequent reshuffle of the
leftist coalition also dampened its image.
</P>
<P>
In last month's election, the AWS secured 33.8 percent of the
vote, beating the ruling SLD by a margin of 6.7 percentage points,
to become the biggest party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The AWS has been negotiating with the Freedom Union since the
election to form a coalition, and the little-known Buzek was
presented as a candidate for prime minister after Solidarity chief
Marian Krzaklewski refused to take the premiership himself.
</P>
<P>
Buzek, 57, once a researcher at the Institute of Chemical
Engineering under the Polish Academy of Sciences, joined the
Solidarity when it is founded in 1980.
</P>
<P>
However, he was not a prominent politician before being elected
member of the parliament in September.
</P>
<P>
After his nomination, Buzek said the new government's
priorities will include developing economy under social
stabilization, and seeding up negotiations of Poland's entry into
the NATO and the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
