<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: As Ross Comes, Israel, PNA Have Differing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 18 (Xinhua) -- As Israel and the
Palestinians await United States peace envoy Dennis Ross' visit,
they have one thing in common - hoping the envoy would pressure
the other side into making concessions.
</P>
<P>
Aside from this, however, their expectations for Ross'
mediation mission are generally differing, perhaps as wide as they
used to be.
</P>
<P>
Ross is due here Sunday in a new bid to advance the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process which had just jump started
following a seven-month freeze. But progress seems hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming Ross' return to the region, the Palestinian
Legislative Council on Friday said it expected that Ross would
shift his focus from Palestinian National Authority's (PNA)
crackdown on Islamic militants to halting Israeli settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
Senior PNA negotiator Saeb Erekat said Ross should deliver on
the agenda that the PNA agreed with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright during her visit here last month and on an end
to Israel's "unilateral steps," including settlement expansion,
confiscation of Palestinian land and demolition of Palestinian
homes.
</P>
<P>
Erekat also demanded Israel proceed with the scheduled further
troop redeployments in the West Bank in accordance with signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Under a Note for Record attached to the Hebron redeployment
deal signed in January, Israel should have completed the first two
of the three-phase redeployments in the West Bank by early
September.
</P>
<P>
But the pullbacks were never carried out because the PNA
refused to accept Israel's unilateral definition of the scope of
troop evacuation. Israel offered to pull out of 2 percent of the
West Bank in the first stage in March, far below what the PNA
expected.
</P>
<P>
Israel, on the other hand, hopes Ross will force the PNA into
waging a consistent war against Islamic militant groups dedicated
to terror attacks on Israel. The Islamic Resistance Movement Hamas,
for example, is responsible for the two latest suicide attacks in
Jerusalem which killed 25 people and wounded more than 300 others.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was quoted by Israel
Radio as saying today that Israel will not hand over more land to
the PNA unless he is satisfied with the PNA's fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
His media adviser, David Bar-Illan, said that top on the agenda
should be the discussion on the PNA's "failure" to take real
actions to dismantle the infrastructure of Islamic militant groups.
</P>
<P>
On the settlement issue, Bar-Illan said Israel was willing to
discuss the definition of "time-out" as called for by
Albright. Moreover, the two sides would also discuss Israel's
proposal for conducting the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel aspires to open the final-status talks immediately,on
the most sensitive issues of Jerusalem, final borders and return
of Palestinian refugees, because this will give it more bargaining
chips by skipping troop redeployments under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
Israeli settlement activities have been the leading obstacle
to any progress in the peace process; the success of Ross' mission
and the Israeli-Palestinian talks seems largely contingent on whether
Israel is willingness to call a freeze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0120 </DOCNO>
