<HEADLINE> Ma's New Protege Threats World Record in 1,500 meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Jiang Bom, new protege of
China's famous track coach Ma Junren, launched her fierce attacks
against the world record by clocking three minutes 50.98 seconds
in the women's 1,500 meters here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Her winning mark at the on-going National Games was only 0.52
seconds short of the world mark of 3:50.46 set by her teammate Qu
Yunxia four years ago in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"I am surprised to win the gold because I only competed in the
National Games as a substitute," said the 20-year-old runner at
the post-match press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Although we (Liaoning) had eight runners in the finals, we did
not set up any tactics, and I encouraged myself to run my best,"
said Jiang, who became one of the most promising runners within
Ma's Family after Wang Junxia and Liu Dong broke away from the
controversial coach in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"I dedicated my gold to coach Ma," said Jiang, "he was very
strick in our training, but very kind and careful in taking care
of our lives off the track."
</P>
<P>
All the top six places were swept by Ma's disiciples while
world record-holder Qu Yunxia finished in the eighth place after
she was elbowed to the floor in the 300-meter mark.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuemei of Sichuan province run her best of 10.79 seconds to
beat her newly-created Asian mark of 10.90 set up in the heats on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I am very, very surprised to break the Asian record as I would
feel satisfied to finish within the top three," said the
20-year-old sprinter who clocked 10.90 seconds in the heats to
better the Asian mark of 11.02 set up by Liu Xiaomei four years
ago in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"I had no secrets in improving my speed except through hard
training," said Li who made her international debut in the World
Athletics Championships in Greece in August wherein she failed to
make the finals.
</P>
<P>
"I was relatively weak in the starting-off and I have paid keen
attention upon it in my training," said Li.
</P>
<P>
Former Asian record holder Liu Xiaomei of Sichuan finished
second in 10.89, also surpassing the previous Asian mark.
</P>
<P>
The women's 100-meter hurdle was won by another Sichuan entry
of Zeng Yan who clocked 12.74 seconds, beating teammate Liu Jing
to second in 12.76 and national-record holder Zhang Yu to third in
12.84.
</P>
<P>
Li Jin of Liaoning province clocked 50.01 seconds to win the
women's 400-meter title, beating veteran Du Xiujie of Guangdong to
second in 50.87.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100-meter title was taken by Zhou Wei of Guangdong
province in 10.22, while a national record was set up in the men's
400-meter finals which was won by Han Chaoming of Guangdong in
45.46 seconds which overpassed the previous mark of 45.85.
</P>
<P>
National champion Song Mingyou of Shandong province beat two
rivals from Liaoning to retain his title by clocking 2:36.54 in
the men's 1,500 meters.
</P>
<P>
All the seven finishers in the event surpassed the listed
national record of 3:40.93 set up by Mo Weiguo at the Hiroshima
Asian Games in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus Claims 43 Percent of World Passenger Plane Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Airbus Consortium
today said it has received orders for building 249 new passenger
planes in the first nine months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The orders, said the world's second largest civilian aircraft
manufacturer headquartered in France, accounted for 43 percent of
the orders placed worldwide during the nine-month period.
</P>
<P>
And the international market share is expected to further go up
to 45 percent by the end of the year, inching closer toward to the
multi-national group's goal for 50 percent by 2002, Airbus said.
</P>
<P>
Among new orders this year, 190 were for the A319, A320 and
A321 models, and 52 were for the A330/A340 long-haul versions.
</P>
<P>
The biggest buyers were from the United States, with a lease
operation, known as ILFC, ordering 65 planes, and the American
West and Northwest airlines ordering 22 and 50 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boeing, the U.S.-based world No.1 aerospace builder,
received 322 orders, or 55.4 percent of the world market volume,
and McDonnell Douglas, also of the United States, got 10 orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
