<HEADLINE> Ma Junren Angry at Slip of World Records in National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Aiming to break the world
records in the women's 1,500 meters, Chinese legendary coach Ma
Junren kept complaining of a "plot" conducted by rivals of his
proteges in the track competitions here Saturday afternoon at the
Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
"Without the accident, three of my disciples were sure to break
the world record. It's a pity for Liaoning, and a pity for China,"
complained coach Ma Junren who sat in the stands with a watch in
his hands during the competitions.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Bo, one of Ma's promising runners, clocked three minutes
50.98 seconds to take the title, with only 0.52 seconds shy of the
world record of 3:50.46.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Qu Yunxia accidently fell to the track in
the 300-meter mark in a body conflict with runners from Henan
province, distracting the attention of other runners, including
Ma's seven proteges in the 12-member finals.
</P>
<P>
"It's a plot of those opponents to stop my disciples from
breaking the world record," coach Ma shouted in his hoarse voice
to reporters who eventually spotted out the lengendary coach in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
The top six places were all swept by his proteges of Ma's
Family, and Qu Yunxia still finished eighth in 3:57.83 after the
accident.
</P>
<P>
"Jiang Bo, Qu Yunxia and Lang Yinglai are the odds-on
candidates to break the world record in the finals," said coach Ma.
</P>
<P>
Despite of injuries, Qu Yunxia has retained her form in the
altitude training prior to the Games, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
And eventual winner Jiang Bo also confirmed Ma's point in a
separate press conference, saying "she (Qu) was better than me in
the training. For me, it's a surprise to win the title as I was
only a substitute before the National Games."
</P>
<P>
Although he kept a low-key note prior to the Games, few people
took seriously the words when Ma said he was only a chef and a
driver at the Games, and only set his sights upon the 2,000
Olympic Games for a miracle.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago in Beijing, his two protegees of Wang Junxia and
Qu Yunxia broke three world records in the women's 10,000, 3,000
and 1,500 meters, with Wang achieving a golden double in the first
two events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
