<HEADLINE> US Official's Visit to Pak Focuses on Pak-India Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming visit to
Pakistan by U.S. Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs
Thomas Pickering will focus on Pakistani-Indian relations, the
Kashmir issue and Afghanistan, a Foreign Office spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Describing the visit as "an essential element of the renewed
American focus on South Asia", the Foreign Office spokesman said
that "the United States regards Kashmir a disputed territory and
has urged for a peaceful solution of the problem in accordance
with the wishes of the people of Jammu and Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
Pickering will be visiting Pakistan from October 18-21 for
comprehensive discussions with Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad on bilateral matters as well as regional and global
issues of mutual interest, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has its own position and we appreciate the
fact that the United States considers Kashmir as a disputed
territory," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. under secretary of state is expected to call on
Pakistani President Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The relations between Pakistan and the United States have been
traditionally friendly and based on shared perceptions," the
Spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani foreign secretary and Pickering are expected to
review the "entire spectrum of Pakistan-US relations from a long
term perspective," he said.
</P>
<P>
This review, the spokesman added, will be aimed at reinforcing
bilateral ties in multiple fields with a special focus on mutually
beneficial economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Pickering's visit will pave the way and set the agenda for the
imminent visits of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
President Bill Clinton, he said.  
</P>
