<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Aid Sent to Southern Sudan's Juba City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- A convoy of barges chartered
by the World Food Program (WFP) left Malakal this week with
urgently needed food aid for Juba, the largest city in the
war-torn southern Sudan, said a WFP report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The WFP barge convoy to Juba is the first to the city this
year and came after months of delays largely due to insecurity in
the region and particularly along the Nile River, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The convoy, carrying a total of 2,664 tons of food aid, is
expected to reach its final destination in mid November.
</P>
<P>
A WFP team aboard the barge will distribute the food aid along
the Nile River and cross frontlines to reach about 374,000 hungry
people living in areas either under the control of the Sudanese
government or the rebel Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
Fighting between the government and rebel forces around Juba
has created chronic food shortages for the city's population of
185,000.
</P>
<P>
It was said that most of the Juba people have been forced to
flee their homes and have been left with no access to
agricultural land, making them rely heavily on food assistance.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has provided emergency assistance to more than 2.6
million war-affected Sudanese, 2.2 million of them living in
southern Sudan, since the beginning of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
