<HEADLINE> Vietnam's PM Urges Effective Use of Investment in Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai has called for more effective use of investment to boost
industrial growth, the Vietnamese press reported today.
</P>
<P>
While inspecting the Industry Ministry on Thursday, Phan Van
Khai asked the ministry to balance the distribution of investment
funds among key economic sectors and between rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who took office last month, stressed that
priority should be given to processing industries, particularly
for agricultural products, to help increase farmers' earnings.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that money must first of all be put into
profitable sectors capable of retrieving capital investment.
</P>
<P>
In terms of where money should be invested, Phan Van Khai said
economically underdeveloped areas should get it first.
</P>
<P>
During the inspection, he asked the Industry Ministry to
improve exports qualitatively and quantitatively, so as to pave
way for the country's entry into the Free Trade Area of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Official data showed that Vietnam's industrial growth remained
slow in recent months, particularly in major industrial centers
such as Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City, Haiphong, and the provinces of
Dong Nai and Khanh Hoa.
</P>
<P>
Unless remarkable changes are made in the industrial sector,
the prime minister said, the growth of the sector itself and the
national economy as a whole will be limited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
