<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China to Further Opening-up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- China is to actively promote
the development of an economy featuring foreign co-operation to
steadily advance economic internationalization according to the
trans-century strategy set by the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China held in Beijing last month.
</P>
<P>
Since China started to open to the outside world in 1978, its
opening-up efforts in different regions are becoming balanced, and
an all-dimension opening-up pattern has been formed preliminarily.
</P>
<P>
The construction and development of special economic zones
(SEZ) and opening-up zones have prompted the creation of a group
of regional economic growth centers, vigorously bringing along
opening up across the country.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the 1980s, the south China region became
the first to open to the outside world, featuring the rapid growth
of external trade and utilization of overseas funds. The region
prompted the development of the whole eastern coast, creating the
first wave of opening up in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1990s, opening-up of the hinterland
has been improved with that of Shanghai's Pudong area, and areas
along the Yangtze River, the borderline and transport trunk lines.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a diversified and all-dimension opening-up
pattern has not only vigorously advanced regional economic
development, but also played an irreplaceable role in promoting
the growth and quality of the economic sector concerning
international co-operation and of the national economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Opening-up has promoted the development of the domestic
economy, with overseas resources and markets contributing more and
more to China's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991-1995 period, one percentage point growth in export
volume brought about 0.2 percentage points growth in GDP. The
development of external trade not only expands the demand of the
domestic market, exerting an important influence on prompting
economic growth, but also plays an increasingly significant role
in balancing the relations between domestic supply and demand, and
adjusting the pace of economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China to Further Opening-up (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a result, China will deepen the reform of its foreign trade
management system to establish a system that tallies with the
socialist market economic system and international norms,
participate in the international multi-lateral trade system and
multi-lateral economic co-operation in the Asia-Pacific region,
strive to reach the market access standards in line with China's
economic development level, and play a bigger role in influencing
the international "game rules."
</P>
<P>
In the course of further opening up, China must gear its
foreign trade and economic cooperation system and policy
adjustment means to international practices to form a standardized
environment for economic internationalization.
</P>
<P>
There remains room for further development, though China has
made quick steps in utilization of overseas funds. At present, the
industrial output value of overseas-funded businesses accounts for
about 15 percent of the national total. If only the part
corresponding to the shares of overseas investors in the
businesses is calculated, the proportion is only about six
percent. And for the tertiary industry, the proportion of the
added value of overseas-funded businesses to the national total is
only three percent.
</P>
<P>
While expanding the fields for overseas investment, China must
pay more attention to investment structure.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to encourage overseas businesses to invest
in agriculture, infrastructure, export-oriented manufacturing, and
rising industries representing the direction of development in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Use of overseas investment in the ordinary processing business
must focus on structure adjustment, enhancement of standards of
the technology introduced, nurturing China's own name-brand
products, and improvement of its own capacity in developing new
technology.
</P>
<P>
The service and trade fields must focus on steady and orderly
opening up to overseas investors, and the country must
appropriately control overseas investment in the real estate and
financial industries to prevent risks incurred by excessive
speculation.
</P>
<P>
China must stick to the principle of "market in exchange for
technology" in using foreign funds, for the improvement of the
contribution of technology to its economic growth and the overall
economic efficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China to Further Opening-up (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the country's total investment, overseas capital has become
an important source of funds for different sectors and regions. In
1996, the proportion of overseas investment to domestic fixed
investment reached 19.2 percent, that of the industrial output
value of overseas-funded enterprises to the national total 15
percent, and that of the export volume of such enterprises 21.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
These figures indicate that the development of overseas-funded
businesses has considerably promoted the adjustment of and
increase in the domestic economy, especially those of industry.
</P>
<P>
Adherence to the opening-up policy is made essential by China's
needs to promote domestic economic development and adjust its
economic structure. China's basic conditions require that it
should actively develop and utilize overseas resources and
markets, step up external exchanges and cooperation in a
multi-leveled and diversified way.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the requirement of a transition of the economic
development pattern and the current level of its opening-up,
China's opening-up process has entered a new stage, which is
featured by the co-existence of development and readjustment.
</P>
<P>
The main characteristics of the new stage include: reliance on
further optimization of its industrial structure and improvement
of quality efficiency to expand the utilization of the
international market and resources; improvement of standards,
expansion of fields and diversification of the participation in
international labor division; deepening of structural reform and
corresponding adjustment of policy to continue to seek
multi-lateral international and regional economic development.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of external trade has remarkably enhanced the
dependence of Chinese economy on the international market. In
1996, China's total foreign trade volume accounted for 35.5
percent of its GDP, which represented a fairly high level in the
world.
</P>
<P>
While expanding foreign trade which centers on improving
economic performance, it is necessary to adhere to the strategy of
giving priority to product quality and to improve the country's
status in international labor division. It is also necessary to
stick to the implementation of a multi-market strategy to expand
the international market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
