<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Take Measures to Curb Traffic Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is going
to intruduce stringent measures to curb road traffic accidents
which claimed an average of 1000 lives every year, according to
Times of Zambia today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Kafula Ng'andu, acting permanent
secretary of the Ministry of Communications and Transport, as
saying here Friday that the government has decided to introduce
breathalyzers in random tests of drivers, in addition to several
other measures that are being designed to make the provision of
safe roads in Zambia more meaningful.
</P>
<P>
Culprits will, on conviction, receive punishment in form of
commuinity manual work, said Ng'andu.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on road safety which attracted representatives
from the Lusaka city council, Zambia police and relevant
government departments, Ng'andu disclosed that Zambia currently
loses around 30 billion kwacha (about 22.75 million U.S. dollars)
representing two percent of the country's Gross Domestic Product
(GDP).
</P>
<P>
About 1000 people are killed while another 5500 are injured in
road traffic accidents in Zambia every year.
</P>
<P>
"The causative factors are varied, but drunk driving and the
poor state of our roads are among the chief culprits in road
accidents," Ng'andu stressed.
</P>
<P>
He told participants that Zambia has also shaped a road safety
policy reform plan aimming at reducing road traffic accidents by
10 percent in the next few years and a further 20 percent will be
achieved by the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
Other measures that the government is yet to introduce include
the commitment of 5 percent fuel levy to road accident reduction
and engineering, and funding safety publicity from resources from
motor vehicle safety levy, said Times of Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
