<HEADLINE> S. Africa Pledges to Promote Ties with Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 18 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has said that his country is firmly committed to
expanding trade and investment ties with Tanzania and other
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a banquet in honor of former Tanzanizan president
Julius Nyerere at weekend, Mandela said to promote the transfer
of skills and technology, and to do everything possible to
promote the development of local business would be in the
interest of the African region.
</P>
<P>
He said he would like to see an expansion of South African
business involvement in Tanzania along such lines.
</P>
<P>
In response, Nyerere said South Africa should work together
with other African countries south of the Sahara to forge a
regional economy able to compete with international business."
</P>
<P>
"South Africa will not make it alone, we have to work
together," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who arrrived here on Wednesday, launched the Mwalimu
Nyerere Foundation, a non-political development body at a
function in Johannesburg last night after meeting Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam-based foundation would encourage and assist
development programs in Africa as well as attempt to forge peace
through negotiation, he said. 
</P>
