<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Africa Spearheading Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The delegates from more than 20
African countries have held recently in Harare a malaria control
workshop to discuss the present endemic situation in the
continent and special malaria control plans at country level.
</P>
<P>
They are determined to make the utmost effort to fight against
the plague.
</P>
<P>
Malaria continues to be one of the most serious public health
problems and a major obstacle to social and economic development
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 270-480 million cases that occur every year in
Africa, 140-280 million cases are children under the age of five
years. It is estimated that in highly endemic areas, a child
under five years of age in Africa will suffer from five to six
episodes of malaria every years.
</P>
<P>
The annual death-toll from malaria in Africa is estimated to
be 1.5 to 2.7 million out of which one million are children under
the age of five years. 17 to 39 percent of hospital deaths in
endemic areas are attributable to malaria.
</P>
<P>
Factors contributing to the present situation include
extension of malaria into some areas that were free or with low
risk of malaria in countries such as Burundi, Madagascar, Saotome
and Principe and the increasing rate of urbanization in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Malaria epidemics are on the increase in Africa, particularly
in highland and desert fringe localities and among non-immune
migrant labourers and refugees who reside in malaria endemic
areas. In recent years, a number of epidemics are also reported
from areas previously known to be malaria free.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, 1995 and 1996, a series of malaria epidemics were
reported from a number of countries in east and southern Africa
with unacceptable level of deaths in all age groups.
</P>
<P>
These waves of frequent epidemics in Africa are associated
with large scale population movements from non-malarious into
malarious areas, construction of dams and irrigation schemes,
major rural development projects and environmental changes
favorable for mosquito breeding and disease transmission.
</P>
<P>
A new but alarming development in Africa is that an increasing
number of older age groups are also developing severe malaria and
thereby dying from the disease.
</P>
<P>
Malaria has a direct negative impact on agricultural
productivity since the peak of malaria transmission coincides
with the active agricultural period such as field preparation,
planning, and harvesting.
</P>
<P>
This negative economic impact for Africa, south of the Sahara,
was estimated in 1987 at 800 million U.S. Dollars and 1.7 billion
U.S. Dollars in 1995. At the current trend, this loss is
expected to double in the next five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Africa Spearheading Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 18 (Xinhua) -- In the 1950s, the World Health
Organization (WHO) launched a global campaign to eradicate
malaria in Europe, North America, some parts of Asia, former
Soviet Union and Australia through large scale insecticide
spraying and case detection and treatment.
</P>
<P>
However, not much was done for and by Africa where 90 percent
of the world's malaria cases and deaths occur.
</P>
<P>
The malaria situation in Africa continued to worsen but there
was no active initiative to control this scourge until the
adoption of the regional malaria control strategy at the
inter-regional WHO conference held in Brazzaville in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, WHO has organized activities to strengthen
national capacities in policy formulation, planning, monitoring
and evaluation of national malaria control programs.
</P>
<P>
The regional task force on malaria established in April 1995,
has been given the responsibility of monitoring the progress of
implementation of malaria control activities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The task force also has the role of mobilizing and
coordinating resources for the implementation of malaria control
activities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many malaria endemic countries of the region have
developed malaria control plans of action and are at various
levels of implementation. Technical guidelines have been produced
and made available to member states. Training activities for
district health workers are being carried out in almost all
countries.
</P>
<P>
The results of large scale research studies on impregnated
bednets and other materials from Gambia, Ghana, Burkina-Faso and
Kenya have shown that the use of these materials can reduce
childhood mortality by 25 to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Currently 27 countries are promoting the use of insecticide
impregnated materials, mostly bednets.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase support for malaria control in Africa,
WHO's director general made available 18 million U.S. Dollars to
support the process of accelerated implementation of malaria
control programs in the African region in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
