<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Not to Request U.S. Non-NATO Ally Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chile will not ask for the
special non-NATO ally status granted to Argentina by the United
States on Thursday, the Chilean foreign minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Argentina gained the status for its participation in several
peace operations, Jose Miguel Insulza told reporters when asked
about the decision by U.S. President Bill Clinton in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, now visiting Argentina, granted his host the status as
an ally outside the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
But on Chile's part, Insulza explained, "we did not go to the
Gulf, did not sent troops to Haiti, or soldiers to Bosnia, so we
cannot demand recognition for things we have not done."
</P>
<P>
The largely symbolic status as a special ally would give
Argentina priority access to U.S.-made weapons, ammunition and
spare parts, and more U.S. cooperation in military training.
</P>
<P>
Under the Foreign Assistance Act of 1961, the U.S. president
has the right to designate close military allies, a status that
does not require U.S. help in case of attacks, but allows the
allies to buy excess U.S. weapons.
</P>
<P>
Countries already designated as close non-NATO U.S. allies are
Israel, Egypt, Jordan, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said Chile has already expressed its policy about peace
operations, and its troops are "available for peace maintenance
operations, but not for peace imposition, meaning to separate
warring factions, and for verifying that the peace agreements
already reached are complied with."
</P>
<P>
Asked if Chile had told the United States about its refusal to
be a special non-NATO ally, Insulza stated that "we have no reason
whatsoever for communicating this officially." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0151 </DOCNO>
