<HEADLINE> Uganda's Foreign Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's foreign reserves have
risen to 621 million U.S. dollars from 572.3 m dollars recorded
three years ago, reported the local daily The Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Uganda's status of economy report of September 1997
was quoted as saying that this represents 61.7 percent increase
in the last ten years, adding that reserves as at 1986 when the
current Museveni's government came to power stood at below 384 m
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the other front, Uganda's current account deficit moved
from 228 m dollars (equivalent of 8.91 percent of gdp) in 1995/96
to 224 m dollars (8.4 percent of gdp) in 1996/97, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
This improvement has resulted mainly from the growth in
merchandize exports (8.2 growth) led by gold which has almost
tripled from 35.15 m dollars in 1995/96 to an estimated 101 m
dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
To this effect the country's economy according to the report,
shows a vibrant edge.
</P>
<P>
Non-monetary gdp has however, shown a steady decline over the
last ten years down from 35 percent in 1987 to 24 percent in
1996, the report said, adding this probably is an indication of
increased absorption of the non-monetary sector into in monetary
sector (marketisation) rather than an indication of declining
income.
</P>
<P>
The share of agriculture in total gdp, has maintained a steady
decline from 55 percnet in 1987 to 44 percent in 1996 due to bad
weather and the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The document pointed out that the increasing share of
manufacturing, construction and trade has case to smile for.
</P>
<P>
The country's annual headline inflation rate rose to 10
percent in April this year and 11.8 percent in May from about 6
-7 percent until March this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign exchange inflows into Uganda have grown from
1,632.64 m dollars in 1995/96 to an estimated 1,810 million
dollars for 1996/97, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
