<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland's New constitution Takes Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Poland's new constitution, the
first since the country's drastic change in 1989, went into effect
today to institutionalize a Western-style democracy.
</P>
<P>
Passed by the parliament in April and approved in a referendum
in May with 52.1 percent of the votes, the constitution was signed
by Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski on July 16.
</P>
<P>
By law, it came into effect three months after the formal
presidential endorsement.
</P>
<P>
The constitution reaffirms the separation of the three
government branches -- the legislative, executive and judicial --
as the country's basic political system.
</P>
<P>
It weakens the presidency by allowing the parliament to
override presidential veto by three-fifths of votes in the House
of Representatives rather than the previous two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
It also provides that the president of the republic is elected
by popular vote to serve a term of five years, during which he or
she appoints the prime minister who in turn nominates a cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the parliament comprises the 460-seat House of
Representatives and the 100-seat Senate popularly elected under a
proportional representative system for a term of four years.
</P>
<P>
The constitution defines the country's economic system as the
one based on economic freedom, private ownership, and on the
unity, dialogue and cooperation of various "social partners."
</P>
<P>
The charter and guarantees the freedom of religious believes,
and provides, among other civil rights, the universal access to
free health care and free education for citizens under age 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
