<HEADLINE> Philippines to Hold Satellite Symposium on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The First Satellite Symposium on
Children, Youth and AIDS (acquired immunodefficiency syndrome) in
Asia and the Pacific will be held on October 22-25 in metropolitan
Manila, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is a prelude to the 4th International Congress on
AIDS in Asia and the Pacific to be held on October 25-29 in the
capital city.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the symposium is "Building Stronger Partnerships
for Children and Youth affected by HIV/AIDS," Dr. Ofelia Monzon,
president of the AIDS Society of the Philippines, was quoted as
saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Monzon, who is also chairperson of the forthcoming
international congress on AIDS, said the symposium shall focus on
children and youth especially those infected by HIV and AIDS. HIV
is human immunodefficiency virus that can cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is aimed to ensure the protection of children and
youth's rights, needs and interests, and affirm the critical role
of the youth in the prevention and control of the spread of
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates by the Joint United Nations Program on
HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), there are already 25,000 cases of HIV/AIDS in
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS' estimates also show that by the end of 1997, some
one million children worldwide will be living with HIV. In 1996
alone, of the 1.5 million people who died of AIDS, about 350,000
were children under the age of 15.  
</P>
</TEXT>
