<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Buries Guevara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Cuba today buried the legendary
Argentine-born Cuban guerrilla leader Ernesto "Che" Guevara 30
years after he was killed trying to start revolution in Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
With President Fidel Castro's presence, the funeral took place
in the Revolution Square of the central city of Santa Clara, where
Guevara's remains were buried in a specially built mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
Castro praised the man, his lieutenant in the struggle leading
to Cuba's 1959 revolution, as a moral giant in his tribute.
</P>
<P>
The image of Guevara, the president said, would grow as the
world was blighted with injustice, exploitation, inequality,
unemployment, poverty, hunger and misery.
</P>
<P>
Guevara, an Argentine-born doctor, was captured by Bolivian
troops on October 8, 1967, while leading an abortive uprising
there, and was executed on the following day.
</P>
<P>
His remains, flung into a secret mass grave near a Bolivian
town, were unearthed and returned to Cuba three months ago.
</P>
<P>
Castro ended his tribute by repeating, "until victory always,"
Guevara's famous words in his farewell letter to the Cuban leader
when he left the island in 1965 to try to export revolution abroad.
</P>
<P>
After Castro's tribute, officers of the Revolutionary Armed
Forces placed the caskets of Guevara and six of his comrades in a
mausoleum built under Guevara's monument.
</P>
<P>
The other six -- four Cubans, a Bolivian and a Peruvian -- died
with Guevara on the Bolivian mission.
</P>
<P>
Castro lit the eternal flame of the mausoleum and then soldiers
went on a grand parade. More than 100,000 Cubans, waving flags and
portraits of Guevara, called out "until victory always."
</P>
<P>
Factory sirens, car horns and cannon volleys blared out across
the island in a minute's tribute after the funeral.
</P>
<P>
Santa Clara, 270 kilometers southeast of Havana, was captured
by Guevara on January 1959 in a battle that was decisive for the
victory of the Cuban revolution against dictator Fulgencio Batista.
</P>
<P>
Guevara's widow and his four children lived in Cuba and his two
brothers and a sister came from Argentina to attend the funeral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
