<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) ended the week sharply lower in reaction to the
announcement of a tough 1998 Budget which however augurs well for
the economy in the longer term.
</P>
<P>
At the close of the week's trading, the 100-quality stocks
Composite Index plunged 39.21 points to 794.80 from last week's
close, the all-share Emas Index fell 8.46 points to 226.16, the
Second Board Index lost 13.57 points to 422.75 while the
Industrial Index was 89.94 points lower at 1,614.87.
</P>
<P>
Trading on KLSE remained dull throughout the week as majority
of players sidelined awaiting the Budget.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the ringgit, up to the 3.22 level against the U.S.
dollar, continued to affect sentiment but the market remained
focused on the Budget amid other regional doldrums which included
falls on Wall Street and the Hong Kong and Singapore bourses.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal Reserve's chairman Alan Greenspan's comment that
Asian governments were to be blamed for the currency woes was said
to have further dampened the market.
</P>
<P>
The main board volume totaled 870.102 million shares valued at
3.767 billion ringgit (about 1.177 billion U.S. dollars) from
1.149 billion shares worth 5.155 billion ringgit (about 1.611
billion U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover was 225.909 million shares valued at
1.940 billion ringgit (about 606.25 million U.S. dollars) compared
with 231.670 million shares worth 2.21 billion ringgit (about
690.625 million U.S. dollars)
</P>
<P>
Off market deals fell to 116.369 million shares valued at 1.102
billion ringgit (about 344.375 million U.S. dollars) against
135.683 million shares worth 1.093 billion ringgit (about 341.562
million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Two counters -- Pernas and Bridgecon -- requested for temporary
suspensions of their shares pending announcements this week when
there was no new listing.
</P>
<P>
This week, the 10 most active counters were MRCB which led the
list at 2.71 ringgit, down two sen, followed by Chase Perdana
which added 1.80 ringgit to 9.25 ringgit, Landmark unchanged at
1.93, RHB Capital down 26 sen to 3.72 ringgit, Land &AMP; General down
nine sen to 1.91 ringgit, Renong and MUI both flat at 3.20 ringgit
and 1.50 ringgit respectively, MBf Capital down 20 sen to 4.24
ringgit, Malaysian Pacific Land down 22 sen to 4.24 ringgit and
Sime Darby down 65 sen to 6.30 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
In terms of volume, MRCB accounted for 61.761 million shares,
Chase Perdana 51.802 million shares, Landmark 38.377 million
shares, RHB Capital 36.566 million shares, Land &AMP; General 27.077
million shares, Renong 26.390 million shares, MUI 23.585 million
shares, MBf Capital 23.124 million shares, Malaysian Pacific Land
17.672 million shares and Sime Darby 14.387 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 42.032 million shares traded,
industrial products 87.948 million shares, construction 71.680
million shares, trading/service 191.197 million shares, IPC 6.908
million shares, finance 185.306 million shares, hotels 39.354
million shares, properties 144.688 million shares, plantation
40.885 million shares, mining 2.726 million shares, trusts 544,000
shares, closed/fund 230,000 shares and loans 16.777 million
shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
