<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week
mixed.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market this week, October-South jumped 80
ringgit (about 25 U.S. dollars) to 1,600 ringgit (about 500 U.S.
dollars) per ton, the highest mark for the week, as the market was
braced by fresh buying.
</P>
<P>
The performance of CPO physicals next week will depend on the
movement of the futures market, dealers said, adding the currency
factor would again be the main factor to judge the price movement
next week.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit was quoted easier at 3.22 to the U.S. dollar at
this week's close.
</P>
<P>
This week on the local metal market, the tin price closed
higher, settling at 17.81 ringgit (about 5.56 U.S. dollars) per kg
against 16.57 ringgit (about 5.17 U.S. dollars) per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
At the close, turnover was moderately lower at 358 tons from
385 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
The performance of the Malaysian tin remained uncertain next
week as it will be underpinned by the ringgit's value with trading
expected to be ranged on moderate interest, a trader said.
</P>
<P>
On Malaysia's rubber market, prices finished the week easier.
Against last week's close, November RSS One wrapped up the week
2.5 sen lower to 279 sen (about 87 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20
dipped 1.5 sen to 278 sen (about 86 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for October 16 was higher at 205.09
Malaysia/Singapore cents per kg against 208.42 cents per kg on
October 9.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average was quoted at 204.67 cents per kg
against 212.59 cents per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
The rubber prices could recover next week on price adjustment
to the local currency, a trader expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
