<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Foreign Exchange Reserves Fall Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The level of Bangladesh' foreign
exchange reserves dipped to 1637.6 million U.S. dollars on
September 22, down by 6.41 percent from 1749.7 million dollars
only a week ago on September 16, the sources from the country's
central bank, the Bangladesh Bank, disclosed here today.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves were 1675 million
dollars on September 4 against 1610 million dollars on August 1.
The foreign exchange reserves, which were 2039 million at the end
of June 1996, nose-dived to 1622 million at the end of June this
year -- a total loss of 417 million in one year, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Finance Minister SAMS Kibria admitted in his own
writ-up published in an English daily September 8 that the
nation's foreign exchange reserves fell to 1617 million in May
1997 from 2074 million in May, 1996, a loss of 457 million or 22
percent in a year.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves amounted to 1.67
billion dollars on August 31 against 1.59 billion on July 31, 1.71
billion on June 30, 1.76 billion on May 30, 1.77 billion on April
30, 1.74 billion on March 31, 1.86 billion on February 28 and 1.98
billion in January, the Bangladesh Bank sources stated.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official at the Foreign Exchange Policy
Department of the Bangladesh Bank, the country's foreign exchanges
reserves have fell far short of the appropriate level as
recommended by the International Monetary Fund, which calls for a
country to retain foreign currencies equivalent to three months'
import bills, as Bangladesh's monthly imports usually amounts to
650 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The present foreign exchange holdings are roughly equivalent
to two and a half months' imports, which should be considered
alarming, since more depletion in the coming months is inevitable
because of growing import demands, particularly for luxury goods
and food items," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The official also attributed the depletion in foreign exchange
holdings to the shortfall in aid disbursements and huge import
payments against import bills for luxury goods and food items.
</P>
<P>
The reduced export receipts and large import payments are the
major factors behind depletion in the foreign exchange holdings,
the official added.
</P>
<P>
The remittances sent by the country's wage earners' from abroad
is one of the major sources of foreign exchange, the official
pointed out, but a downward trend has prevailing in the wage
earners' remittances since January this year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, visits by the ministers and high officials of the
government to foreign countries is also another factor behind the
depletion of foreign exchange reserves, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The government has been making constant efforts to improve the
foreign exchange holdings level under immense pressure from the
donors but it has apparently failed to overcome the sluggish
situation, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Meeting Agrees to Aid Albania With Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A strategy for providing
"conditional" aid to help reconstruct Albania's economy was
decided at an international conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from donor countries, the European Union and
the World Bank agreed to condition further aid to Albania on its
immediate political reforms and full adherence to market rules.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, convened to prepare an upcoming donors'
meeting, the World Bank foresaw an international commitment of 1.5
billion U.S. dollars to Albania over a seven-year period.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Premier Fatos Nano called on the donor countries to
provide some 350 million dollars for his country -- 100 dollars
per capita -- for the next 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
But Nano added that he was not asking for money divorced from
specific projects after his 100 dollars per capita plan was
immediately dismissed by Dini as "unrealistic."
</P>
<P>
Dini, who chaired the meeting, said Albania had signed a letter
of understanding with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in
which fiscal and monetary policing measures are listed.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting, aimed at paving the way for a donors'
conference to be held in Brussels on October 22, was held also to
assess the progress made by Albania's new leadership.
</P>
<P>
Satisfied with what the new Albanian government had done to
restore stability, participants agreed to hold a similar meeting
in Rome or Tirana to find better ways to help Albania.
</P>
<P>
Albania descended into chaos in early March when protests
triggered by the collapse of pyramid investment schemes, in which
thousands of Albanians lost their life saving, mushroomed across
the country.
</P>
<P>
The protests turned violent after armed rebels looted army
depots and took over several towns in the south.
</P>
<P>
The country was back on track only when a new government was
formed after former president Sali Berisha, widely blamed for the
collapse of the investment schemes, resigned in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Celebrates 1st Anniversary of Constitutional Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The existence of the Ukrainian
Constitutional Court showed Ukraine's commitment to democratic
reforms, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma said today.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony commemorating the first anniversary of the
Constitutional Court, Kuchma said the court served as a guarantee
that Ukraine would remain on the road to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma warned against attempts to exert pressure on the court,
which he described as the sole organ protecting the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, the court was used as a buffer in political
conflicts between the president and the Supreme Soviet, or the
Ukrainian parliament.
</P>
<P>
The parliament has accused Kuchma many times as
unconstitutional when the president vetoed parliamentary bills,
such as the Law on Local Administration.
</P>
<P>
However, the court so far has judged no case as
unconstitutional, which in some way helped the president. As a
result, the parliament tried in early September to weaken the
Constitutional Court through an amendment to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The amendment, which would give the parliament a status as the
final arbiter of the constitutionality of legislation, failed to
pass through the Supreme Soviet.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma also declared at the celebration that the court should
not be drawn into political struggle that is currently gathering
pace as the March 1998 parliamentary elections come in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Backs Slovenia's Bid for NATO, EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy today reiterated its support
for Slovenia's early entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini recommitted the support while
holding talks with his new Slovenian counterpart Boris Frlec, who
is here to attend a ministerial conference on Albania.
</P>
<P>
Dini hoped that Slovenia's bid for NATO and EU memberships
would be discussed early next year.
</P>
<P>
A NATO summit in Madrid in July decided to invite Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to enter into NATO. But split
remained among NATO members over the enlargement pace.
</P>
<P>
Italy and some other NATO members want Slovenia and Romania to
be among the first group of countries to be invited into the
alliance, while the United States prefers a limited group.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the significance of admitting Slovenia and Romania,
Italy held that southern Europe is likely to become the most
complicated and volatile region in the continent, both politically
and economically.
</P>
<P>
At their meeting in Rome, Dini and Frlec also noted the rapid
growth of bilateral ties, fostered in part by the consolidation of
the trilateral relations between Italy, Slovenia and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Dini spoke highly of Slovenia's participation in the
multi-national peacekeeping operation in Albania, and noted that
the Italian government will try its best to protect ethnic
Slovenians residing in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Frlec in turn reiterated the Slovenian government's
determination to protect ethnic Italians in Slovenia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
