<HEADLINE> Indian Exporters Call for Devaluation of Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 18 (Xinhua)-- In view of Pakistan
devaluating its currency by 8 percent on Wednesday, Indian
exporters are clamoring for a similar move, a local newspaper
Business Standard reported here today.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that rice, leather, textiles and garments,
chemicals exports from India would be hit by Pakistan's
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Federation of Indian Export Organizations President Ramu S.
Deora said that he has written to the Reserve Bank of India (RBI)
seeking a devaluation of 5-10 percent of the rupee with the new
credit policy.
</P>
<P>
The exporters also wanted a 4-5 percent difference between the
rate at which export finance is available and the prime lending
rate. They are seeking a cut in the rate of export finance from 11
to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Delhi Exporters Association President S.P. Aggarwal has also
appealed to the government for a devaluation. "This is the second
time Pakistan has devalued its currency- both times by around 8
percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indian government officials admitted that the Pakistani
devaluation could hurt exports of textiles and garments since the
two countries compete in these areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
