<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's 100m Record-Breaker Blamed by Coach after Heats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Li Xuemei shocked by herself
by breaking the women's 100-meter Asian record, but was stunned by
her coach who surprisingly threw the cold water upon his protege
after the heats instead.
</P>
<P>
"Congratulations first," said coach Zhang Rongwei, "But I still
had to blame you. Your record-breaking feat in the heats did no
good for yourself in the finals."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Rongwei butted the 20-year-old sprinter at the track side
on Friday right after the preliminaries as the budding star was
still full of excitement.
</P>
<P>
Li clocked the fastest of 10.90 seconds in the morning's heats
to better the Asian record of 11.02 set by her compatriot Liu
Xiaomei four years ago.
</P>
<P>
While blaming Li for her early exposure, coach Zhang was still
unable to hide his smiles, saying "Li was not the person to be
blamed actually because she was under no pressure in the heats,
which played an important role for her record."
</P>
<P>
"Li originally competed in the hurdles, and I recruited her
into my camp after the Seventh National Games four years ago as
the teenager impressed me deeply in 1990 with her swift set-off,
quick rhythm and fluent movements," Zhang recalled.
</P>
<P>
"She has made steady and promising progresses in the years, she
was surely a good sprinter with great potentials," said the coach.
</P>
<P>
"To predict the finals, I personally think Li is the odds-on
favorite," Zhang said with confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
