<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Scraps Oil Tax Rise Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has revoked
a three-day-old oil price hike decision, according to a government
house press release available today.
</P>
<P>
The one-baht-per-liter oil price increase was introduced on
Tuesday to increase government revenue by 24 billion baht (655
million U.S. dollars) for fiscal 1998, which began on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The government is under pressure of the International Monetary
Fund to maintain a budget surplus of 1 percent of gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
The price hike for petrol and diesel was scrapped on Friday at
a meeting chaired by Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh,
following the public's display of dissatisfaction and threat of
mass demonstrations calling for the prime minister's resignation.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts say the reverse of the decision would do harm
to the government's credibility and could send financial markets
into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
The scrapping of the oil price rise might mean tax increase on
other items or further cuts in government expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cabinet on Friday also decided to delay the
approval of eagerly expected five critical decrees on financial
reform because of "technical errors."
</P>
<P>
The five decrees, expected to be unveiled on Friday, were
designed to establish the financial restructuring authority and
the asset management corporation to manage the 58 suspended
debt-ridden finance firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Hemispheric Free Trade Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton today praised the South Common Market (Mercosur) and again
raised the need to forge a hemispheric free trade alliance.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here with 500 Argentine businessmen, the visiting
U.S. president said Mercosur not only helps expand trade in the
region, but also enhances efforts to promote democracy and peace.
</P>
<P>
Established in December 1994 to promote free trade among its
member countries -- currently Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay, Mercosur is the biggest trade bloc in South America.
</P>
<P>
Trade groups of the similar kind in the west hemisphere are
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the Andean Pact.
</P>
<P>
In his speech today, Clinton asked members of these regional
groups to create the Free Trade Area of Americas (FTAA) covering
800 million people from Alaska of the United States in North
America to the Patagonia in South America.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral economic relations, he said trade between the
United States and Argentina reached 6.8 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, a 152 percent increase over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, U.S. investment in Argentina grew from 2
billion to 12.5 billion dollars during the period of 1990-1996 and
is expected to reach 18 billion dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Argentine President Carlos Menem, the
two presidents expressed willingness to better cooperate in trade.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he is working to convince U.S. Congress to approve
"fast track" trade negotiation authority to dismantle trade
barriers and open U.S. doors to emerging markets in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed new mechanism, Congress has the right to
approve or reject any international trade accord already reached
by the U.S. administration, but can not amend the document.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, here since Wednesday after visiting Venezuela and
Brazil, will end his week-long Latin America tour on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
