<HEADLINE> Thailand May Postpone New Railroad Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's plans for four new
railroad tracks may have to be suspended because of slashed
government budget, according to Saravuth Thammasiri, governor of
the state railway of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The four planned tracks, totaling over 700 kilometers, would
form a network linking the country's special economic zones with
the greater Mekong sub-region in the north and northeast, and the
growth triangle in the south, the Bangkok Post today quotes
Saravuth as saying.
</P>
<P>
The planned route stretches would include a 246-km track from
Phrae to Chiang Rai in the north, a 312-km track from Nakhon
Ratchasima to Mukdahan in the northeast, a 16-km track in Rayong
in the east and a 160-km track from Surat Thani to Phuket in the
south.  
</P>
