<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Firm on Huaihe Treatment Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- With only two and half months
left till the State Council's deadline for limiting discharge of
pollutants in the Huaihe River Valley, the central government has
resolved to ensure that the target is reached on time.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Zhang Kunmin, deputy administrator
of the National Environmental protection Agency of China (Nepa),
as saying that Nepa would soon launch a national drive to force
all enterprises in the Huaihe Valley in east China to step up work
toward the target, and those that cannot clean up must be closed
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the State Council required that all enterprises along
the river treat industrial waste to meet state-set standards by
the end of this year and that the whole river be cleaned up by
2,000.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe Valley is one of the seven major water systems in
the country, and one of its important grain and energy production
bases. It has been seriously contaminated in the past decade with
about half of the 191 rivers in the basin turning black and foul
and having lost their function.
</P>
<P>
Data from Nepa indicate that by the end of August, about 33.6
percent of the 1,562 enterprises with a daily discharge of
wastewater above 100 tons in the four Huaihe Valley provinces -
Anhui, Jiangsu, Henan and Shangdong - have reached the state
target.
</P>
<P>
The program to treat pollution in the valley will cost 27.5
billion yuan (3.2 billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
