<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT, October 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR -- The Mongolian parliament, the Great Hural, Friday
rejected the proposal by the Mongolian People's Revolution Party
(MPRP) that the government resign.
</P>
<P>
The vote, following two days heated debate in the Great Hural,
was participated in by 73 of the 75 parliament members, and ended
with 47 against and 25 for the motion.
</P>
<P>
During the debate, the ruling Mongolian National Democratic
Party argued that the country's economy had started to show
improvements, the result of the government's economic
policies. (Mongolia-Parliament-Vote)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Washington Monument, the towering landmark on
the skyline of the United States' capital, will soon undergo
repairs.
</P>
<P>
Target discount stores are leading a private corporate effort
to pay the five-million-dollar bill for the most extensive
overhaul of the monument since it opened to the public in 1888,
The Washington Post said.
</P>
<P>
Though the monument will close for up to four months early next
year for elevator and climate control repairs, it will remain open
for exterior work that will go on at least until the year 2000.
(US-Washington Monument)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People (NAACP) is backing calls for Merriam-Webster to
revise its dictionary definition of the word "nigger."
</P>
<P>
The Merriam-Webster dictionary's 9th and 10th editions defines
the word as "a black person... usually taken to be offensive."
</P>
<P>
NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said that definition "doesn't say,
`Once used to describe a black person, a slur.' It says, `A black
person.'" (US-Dictionary)
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey, the United States and Britain Friday called
on two warring northern Iraqi parties to respect cease-fire and
immediately stop their fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a written statement that
the three sponsors of the two-year-old Ankara process urged the
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) to withdraw their troops from the conflicting
areas.
</P>
<P>
"The three countries hold that any fighting in this area is
unacceptable," the statement said. (Turkey-Northern Iraq)
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panamanian anti-drug police seized 542 kilograms
of cocaine and detained seven persons in two operations Friday in
the Atlantic coast, according to a police report.
</P>
<P>
Police agents seized 173 kilograms of the drug hidden in 25 air
conditioning appliances in the Alcazar Internacional company
installations in the Colon Customs Free Zone as it was loaded in a
container for shipment to a South American country.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said that seven persons were detained and the
manager of the company is under investigation. (Panama-Drug
Seizure)
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican President Jose Maria Figueres left here
Friday for New York on a three-day visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Figueres, a former West Point student, will make a visit to his
alma mater during his stay in the United States, the Presidential
House announced.
</P>
<P>
Figueres' current trip to the United States had not been
announced previously. (Costa Rica-US-Visit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
