<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Austria to Boost Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and Austria have built a
legal basis for expanding their trade and economic cooperation,
Austrian Finance Minister Rudolf Edlinger said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an economic roundtable, Edlinger said Ukraine and
Austria on Thursday signed an agreement to avoid double taxation,
so as to provide a new impetus for furthering bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Austria's opening of an investment bank in Kiev on
Thursday, Ukrainian Finance Minister Igor Mitiukov said Austrian
bankers and businessmen were among the first to operate in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Edlinger said Ukraine is the second among the
former Soviet republics in priority to Austria and the bilateral
trade turnover reached more than 400 million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Edlinger, here since Thursday for a three-day visit, said his
trip was aimed at establishing contacts with representatives of
Ukrainian ministries and to outline specific cooperation programs.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is experiencing substantial problems in implementing
privatization programs due to shortages of funds, said Mitiukov.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the Austrian investment bank in Ukraine, he
said, is an event of high importance that will attract more
capital inflow and help the growth of trade turnover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
