<HEADLINE> Argentina, U.S. Sign Anti-Drug Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine and U.S.
governments signed a joint statement here today on hemispheric
anti-drug policies.
</P>
<P>
The two governments highlighted in the statement the importance
of international, multilateral and bilateral cooperation in the
war against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their determination to consolidate a strategic
alliance for continuous joint efforts "to finish this terrible
malady that mainly affects younger generations."
</P>
<P>
They emphasized the need to further promote the policies of
balance between the control of the drug supply and the reduction
of the demand, and to forge a hemispheric anti-drug strategy.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed by Barry McCaffrey, director of the
U.S. Office of National Drug Control Policy, and Julio Cesar
Araoz, secretary for Argentina's Prevention of Drug Addiction and
the War Against Drug Trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine and U.S. governments will "strengthen an alliance
of objectives and actions to reach the common target of having the
world free of drugs," the statement said.  
