<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Welcomes Pullout of U.N. Peace-keepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, October 17, (Xinhua) -- Croatia welcomes a United
Nations decision to withdraw 2,000 international peace-keeping
soldiers from its territories before November 15.
</P>
<P>
Neven Jurica, spokesman for the Croatian government, made the
remark at a press conference today referring to the U.N. pullout
from Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision, made by the U.N. Security Council as
recommended by Secretary-General Kofi Annan on June 23, showed
that the peace process in these areas is proceeding smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Under Annan's proposal, the United Nations Transitional
Administration for Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium
(UNTAES) would withdraw its troops from Croatia in two stages.
</P>
<P>
The first stage, already accomplished in July, calls for the
withdrawal of 2,500 soliders; and the second stage, scheduled for
full implementation before November 15, involves 2,000 others.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the second stage, there will be 720 peace-keepers
remaining in Croatia to protect U.N. personnel, equipment and
facilities, and help clean up landmines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
