<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Establishes Part for Returned Students' Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing city has established a
park for Chinese students who have returned from abroad to launch
their own enterprises, according to a report in today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to the development of information
technology and biological engineering technology when new
businesses are established, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Preferential treatment will be given to such enterprises,
including a full rent waiver in the first year, it said.
</P>
<P>
The first of its kind in Beijing, the park was sponsored by the
Beijing Overseas Students Service Center and the Beijing New
Technology Industries Development Experimental Zone.
</P>
<P>
"Statistics indicate that the number of returned students has
been increasing by 13 percent each year, and a lot of those who
studied abroad are viewing Beijing as a more and more attractive
place to establish their careers," the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, many returned students tended to take positions with
joint ventures and foreign companies in China because of the lack
of a suitable climate fro starting their own businesses, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
