<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smog Reduces Visibility to Zero in Cities of Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Choking smog caused by forest
fires in Indonesia returned to several cities on Friday, and the
visibility in one Sumatra town was reported to be reduced to zero.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said here today visibility in several
cities on Sumatra and Kalimantan islands, was between 100 meters
and 500 meters, and more fires were reported on the two islands.
</P>
<P>
Dense smokes from fires on Sumatra and Borneo have spread over
much of Southeast Asia in the past two months, causing widespread
health warnings and being blamed at least partly for an air crash
and ship collisions.
</P>
<P>
"As of early Friday morning, we have received reports which say
visibility in cities such as Palembang, Bengkulu, Jambi and Padang
on Sumatra is between 100 and 500 meters," a Jakarta
Meteorological Department official said.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Padang, west Sumatra, said the city was "dark."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, part of the capital Jakarta was shrouded by thick
haze on Friday, but the official said this was the result of
pollutants rather than smoke from the forest fires.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Forum for Environment (Walhi) estimated earlier
that at least 1.7 million hectares of forests have been damaged by
the fires and the total loss of the fires and haze was 6.2
trillion rupiah (about 1.7 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
