<HEADLINE> Several Countries Join UN to Condemn Colombo Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The governments of United
states, Germany, Britain and Japan have joined the United Nations
to condemn Wednesday's bombing in Colombo and extend their
sympathy to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan strongly condemned the bomb
attack in Colombo, his spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Thursday's
press briefing at UN headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is appalled by the news of the bomb
attack in Colombo and the resulting loss of life and destruction
of property. He strongly condemns this terrorist attack, which
targeted civilian facilities," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A local newspaper quoted its sources in Washington as saying
that the U.S. State Department has released a statement condemning
the Colombo bombing.
</P>
<P>
The statement said: "If the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) was responsible for this indiscriminate attack, it's a
further demonstration of the threat caused by the LTTE to the
security of American nationals."
</P>
<P>
"The threat was a justification for their being designated by
the Secretary of State Madeleine Albright as a terrorist
organization."
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said in a message to Sri
Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar that he "was deeply
distressed to learn about the cowardly and senseless attack on a
hotel in Colombo which claimed so many innocent human victims."
</P>
<P>
In a message to Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said: " I very much deplore the
loss of life and many injuries caused by this appalling incident,
we strongly condemn this terrible attack."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Government in a statement said: "Japan condemns
all forms of terrorism and sincerely hopes the Sri Lankan
Government and its people will continue to make efforts for
realizing everlasting peace, the nation's wholehearted desire, by
overcoming the present tragedy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
