<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Help Indonesia Deal With Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan is prepared to give
technical and financial assistance to Indonesia to help the
country overcome its currency crisis, a senior Japanese official
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese government stands solidly behind Indonesia ...
and is ready to extend bilateral financial or technical assistance
to the country," visiting Japanese Vice Finance Minister for
International Affairs Eisuke Sakakibara said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Japan would back any program endorsed by international
organizations, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
the World Bank (WB) and the Asian Development Bank (ADB) to help
Indonesia recover from the currency turmoil, Sakakibara was quoted
today by Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
IMF delegates and WB and ADB representatives are in Jakarta to
discuss a financial aid package for Indonesia. the IMF-led team
has not announced details of the aid package but analysts
speculate that the assistance would include standby loans worth up
to 12 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sakakibara, who also met members of the IMF-led team during his
Indonesian visit, said assistance from Japan would come after a
decision on an aid package now being put together by the IMF, WB
and ADB.
</P>
<P>
Sakakibara's comments turned the falling markets around,
boosting the rupiah (the national currency) to 3,570 against the
U.S. dollar at the close in Jakarta after hitting a low of 3,710
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The dollar has gained more than 50 percent against the rupiah
since the beginning of this year, making the Indonesian currency
the worst hit in the turbulent region.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts said speculation over details of the IMF-led
assistance to restore confidence in the Indonesian rupiah is
likely to dominate the country's financial markets next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Relief Foundation Helps Poor in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Foundation for
Underdeveloped Regions of China (FURC), a non-governmental
organization established in 1989, is currently carrying out three
major poverty relief projects.
</P>
<P>
The projects focus on the country's southwest and northwest
regions, where most of its poverty-stricken people live, today's
China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Among the 58 million suffering from poverty in China, 20
million are in the southwest, and 10 million in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
The projects involved the creation of arable land by blasting
away rock in the mountainous areas in Guizhou province, clean
drinking water for local residents in Gansu and Shaanxi provinces,
and reconstruction of houses in Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
By March of next year, 667 hectares of land will have been
cleared in Guizhou. By the end of this year, 2,000 water tanks
will have been built in Gansu and Shaanxi, and 1,500 families will
have had houses re-built in Sichuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Leftist Leaders Arrested in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Two leaders of a Philippine
leftist guerrilla group blamed for more than 200 assassinations
have been captured by the military in the central Philippines,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nilo de la Cruz, head of the urban hit squad Alex Boncayao
Brigade (ABB), were arrested in Marilao town, Bulacan province
north of Manila, Thursday night, the reports quoted military
officials as telling reporters Friday.
</P>
<P>
Also apprehended were Arturo Tabara, secretary general of the
Revolutionary Workers' Party, the ABB's political arm, and two
other ABB members, Army chief Lt. Gen. Celmente Mariano said.
</P>
<P>
De la Cruz, carrying a reward of 1.5 million pesos (44,000 U.S.
dollars) on his head, has been hunted for eight years, surrendered
after a brief shoot-out with a team of army intelligence agents
and local police in Marilao town. The intelligence agents had
tailed De la Cruz for nearly three months.
</P>
<P>
From 1986 to 1996, De la Cruz as head of the ABB has directed
the assassination of more than 200 policemen, military personnel
and civilians in Metro Manila, Mariano said.
</P>
<P>
Among the victims were U.S. Army Col. James Rowe, chief of the
Joint U.S. Military Advisory Group, who was killed in a daylight
ambush in April 1989 in Manila.
</P>
<P>
De la Cruz has also been accused of masterminding 30 robberies
and kidnappings in order to raise funds for the operations.
</P>
<P>
The ABB was established in Metro Manila in the early 1980s by
de la Cruz and other members of the Communist Party of the
Philippines (CPP). But in February 1997, the group broke away from
the CPP and its New People's Army due to internal differences.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, President Fidel Ramos ordered a crackdown on
the ABB after local industrialist Leonardo Ty was killed by
suspected ABB members. At least 16 ABB members have been arrested
since then, according to the military.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Posts Savings in Debt Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government posted
savings of 1.696 billion pesos (about 49.9 million U.S. dollars)
in debt service payments in the first nine months of this year,
despite the ill-effect of the peso depreciation and accelerating
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data on the government's cash budget
operations, the total debt service payment for the first three
quarters of the year amounted to 86.794 billion pesos, 1.696
billion pesos lower than the 88.490 billion pesos projected for
the period.
</P>
<P>
Of the 86.794 billion peso debt service payment for the nine
months, 58.341 billion pesos were used to pay interest on both
domestic and foreign obligations, and the rest went to pay for
principal amortization.
</P>
<P>
Government figures show that the government paid 17.342 billion
pesos to service the principal amount of its foreign debt, 2.213
billion pesos more than the programmed payments.
</P>
<P>
Interest payments for the foreign debt were also 0.403 billion
pesos higher than the programmed amount of 12.184 billion pesos.
</P>
<P>
The increase in payments was due to the depreciation of the
peso. The government had assumed debt service payments at a rate
of only 26.54 to the dollar, but the average foreign exchange rate
used when payment was made was placed at 27.52 pesos against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, the increased debt service payments were offset by the
lower debt service payments on principal and interest on
internally generated liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Interest payments for domestic borrowings in the first nine
months of the year were lower by 1.425 billion pesos to 45.754
billion pesos against the target of 47.179 billion pesos.
</P>
<P>
The sharp depreciation of the peso during the last three months
will cost the government much more for the debt payments in the
last quarter of the year. The peso has fallen to 34 against the
dollar from 26.5 since July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
