<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Four million farmers and herdsmen in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region now have access to clean drinking
water, thanks to a 900-million-yuan project initiated three years
ago. The project has involved the building of water plants and
cisterns, drilling of wells, and laying of water pipelines.
</P>
<P>
-- The Eighth National Congress of the China Democratic League
opened in Beijing Friday. The league is one of the eight
non-communist parties in the country. Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun
made a congratulatory address at the congress on behalf of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese swimmer Wu Yanyan broke the world record for women's
200-meter medley in Shanghai on the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- The 23rd IUSSP (International Union for the Scientific Study
of Population) General Population Conference closed Friday in
Beijing. Experts say it's a successful conference that will propel
population studies worldwide into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
-- China successfully launched an ApStar-2R telecommunications
satellite on a Long-March 3b rocket at the Xichang Satellite
Launching Center in southwest Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun, who has made an investigation
tour of northeast China's Liaoning province, urged the agriculture
sector to focus on working for a good harvest next year as an
effort to put the guidelines of the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China into practice.
</P>
<P>
 China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The English-language newspaper frontpaged a press briefing
by Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation Sun
Zhenyu, who painted a rosy picture of Sino-US relations despite
the persistence of certain stumbling blocks.
</P>
<P>
-- China's tax revenue posted rapid growth in the first nine
months this year, outstripping the increase of the nation's gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese and African trade union officials attending a
symposium in Beijing agreed trade unions worldwide should enhance
solidarity and co-operation amid intensifying economic
globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
