<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Reach Agreement Over Shipping Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Japan
reached an agreement to settle their tense shipping dispute today,
two days following the U.S. Federal Maritime Commission (FMC)
threatened to bar Japanese ships from U.S. ports.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both countries noted they have reached an
agreement in principle to give U.S shippers the same access to
Japan's ports that the Japanese enjoy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
U.S. shippers have complained for a long time about burdensome
Japanese port rules that drive up costs.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat, the leader of the
U.S. negotiating team, characterized the deal as a "breakthrough
which we hope will lead to meaningful reform of these restrictive,
costly and prohibitive port practices."
</P>
<P>
The trade dispute flared up dramatically this week when the
FMC, the U.S. independent regulatory organization, decided to bar
container cargo ships from Japan's three major shipping lines from
entering U.S. ports.
</P>
<P>
The ban was scheduled to take effect at midnight Friday, but it
is widely believed here that the FMC would drop its order in wake
of the progress achieved in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Lower-level negotiators were directed to work out the fine
print, a process that the U.S. side estimated might take the
weekend to wrap up.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Japanese agreed to create an
alternative system for U.S. and other foreign carriers to
negotiate for stevedores to unload their ships.
</P>
<P>
The three Japanese shipping lines -- Mitsui O.S.K. Lines, Ltd.,
Kawasaki Kisen Kaisha Ltd., and Nippon Yusen K.K. -- typically
carry containers of boxes that can be loaded onto railroad cars.
These companies were ordered to pay for an estimated 4 million
U.S. dollars in fines that came due at midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Those fines, which is about 100,000 dollars per ship entering a
U.S. port, were imposed starting in September after the U.S.
claimed the Japanese government failed to live up to earlier
commitments to liberalize port practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
