<HEADLINE> Philippines to Safeguard Bank Investments in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is considering putting up safeguards for banks'
securities and stock investments, local newspaper the Philippine
Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Deputy Central Bank Governor alberto Reyes as
saying that one possible safeguard would be to require banks to
set aside additional provisions for possible loss from their
securities and stock investments, especially with the downturn in
the equities market.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that the central bank wants banks to
"mark-to-market" their securities and stocks exposures as the
measure is necessary amid recent ups and downs in the equities
market.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important now because of the present situation in
the stock market," he said, adding the market has been adversely
affected by the on-going currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine stock market has suffered a slump, with the
volatility in the currency market as foreign investors try to
minimize their exposure in the country. The composite index of the
stock market has dropped to around 2000 from above 3000 at the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the declines in the value of banks' stocks, Reyes
said that banks should recognize their losses.
</P>
<P>
He said that based on initial studies, the proposed
provisioning may be charged to bank's operating cost.
</P>
<P>
Reyes admitted that the measures would affect the profitability
of banks as they are expected to provide reserves for these
losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
