<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Governmental Exchanges Crucial Link Between China, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 18 (Xinhua) -- Sino-U.S. relations were
clouded when David Boren, former chairman of the intelligence
committee of the U.S. Senate, visited Beijing for the first time
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Boren came to China at the invitation of a non-governmental
organization -- the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs
(CPIFA) -- because official exchanges were almost non-existent
then.
</P>
<P>
The China he saw was in such contrast to the one that he
learned about through the U.S. media that he said at the end of
his visit: "There has been no trip like this one that my view of a
large country was totally changed by the first visit."
</P>
<P>
Despite subsequent ups and downs in Sino-U.S. relations, the
political communities of the two countries have not stopped
communicating through non-government channels.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Boren's Beijing trip became the prelude to a series of
visits by a large number of U.S. legislators during the summer of
1993 through the spring of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Boren's conclusion, voiced during his visit and widely accepted
in the U.S. political community, was that Sino-U.S. interaction
would be the most important bilateral relations in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
The crucial role of non-government contact became apparent
whenever the two countries were at odds.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, bilateral relations chilled abruptly after the United
States invited Taiwan's Lee Tung Hui to visit. However, on the
invitation of a Chinese non-government organization, a large
number of U.S. legislators and their aides came to China.
</P>
<P>
Among them were such congressional leaders as Robert
Livingston, Bennett Johnston and Nancy Kassenbaum.
</P>
<P>
Through frank and extensive talks with their hosts, these
legislative leaders said that Lee's visit was a mistake. Because
of the legislators' influence, their views received wide attention
in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 through 1996, 34 senators and 46 members of the House
of Representatives visited China on the invitation of the Chinese
People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
As the date of Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the
U.S. approaches, the number of U.S. legislators who have visited
China through non-government channels is increasing. Thirty-five
members of Congress already visited China in the first month of
this year. During their visits, they discussed such issues as
Taiwan, trade, human rights and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental exchanges have maintained an open channel of
communication between the two countries. These exchanges have
created a favorable condition for the improvement and expansion of
official links.
</P>
<P>
One well-known U.S. China expert put forward the idea of
"all-round engagement" during his visit to Beijing in
1994. U.S. President Bill Clinton's administration picked up this
idea in setting the tone of its policy toward China.
</P>
<P>
As the scope of non-government contact between China and the
U.S. expands, even more U.S. leaders are paying private visits to
China. They include former government heads, congressional
members, China experts and representatives from non-government
organizations.
</P>
<P>
China also is sending non-government groups to the U.S., such
as a delegation from the Foundation of Poverty Alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental exchanges have played a role in increasing
mutual understanding and enhancing trust between China and the
U.S. These exchanges have become an indispensable link in
bilateral relations, according to Mei Zhaorong, president of the
Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0224 </DOCNO>
