<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Tumbles Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 17 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks tumbled again
today, dragging the Dow Jones industrial average as much as 211
points lower in the past two sessions.
</P>
<P>
A partial rebound over the last hour reduced much of the
damage, with the Dow halving its loss to 91.85 points and
finishing the week at 7,847.03. The blue-chip barometer suffered a
loss of 198.18, or about 2.5 percent, for the week. Even with the
loss, the Dow is up more than 21 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index also recovered from what could have
been a record one-day slide. It was down more than 53 points
during the afternoon, falling 32.81 to close at 1,666.85.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 11.06 to 944.17,
halving an earlier loss of more than 23 points; and the NYSE
composite index fell 5.74 to 496.56.
</P>
<P>
Small companies could not survive the tumbling either.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 7.87 to
449.29, its first four-session slide since early August. The
American Stock Exchange composite index, which is dominated by
smaller companies, fell 7.50 to 700.88.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a nearly 4-to-1
margin on the NYSE, with its volume hitting 623.25 million shares
as against 595.98 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The markets were also pressured today by news of
bigger-than-expected increases in industrial production and
housing construction during September.
</P>
<P>
Also pressuring stocks today was a potential trade war with
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
