<DOCNO> XIE19971018.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Trade, Landmines to Dominate Chretien's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien left for a visit to Russia today to further bilateral
trade and seek its signature on the landmine treaty.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said earlier this week that his four-day Russia visit,
starting October 18, will focus on "issues such as the treaty to
ban anti-personnel mines, Canada's economic relations with Russia
and cooperation in the Arctic."
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister will be here to re-establish Canada as a
major trading partner, as a G-7 partner and as a member of many
major international organizations," Canadian ambassador to Russia
Anne Leahy was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Canada and Russia has been sluggish in recent
years despite repeated vows by their leaders to double trade from
1995 levels by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Last year, bilateral trade was 781 million dollars (560 million
US dollars). It has increased by 30 percent so far this year,
according to the Canadian government.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Chretien's prime effort is expected to be on
behalf of Bombardier, which is bidding on a Russian contract for
14 executive jets.
</P>
<P>
He will also be pitching Canadian expertise in several planned
Russian megaprojects, including development of a massive gold mine
in Siberia, reports said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the salesman's role, the Canadian prime minister
will press Russian President Boris Yeltsin into signing a treaty
banning anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
"It's a chance for me to persuade the Russians with our project
to ban landmines in the world," Chretien said before he headed to
Moscow today.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has indicated that Russia would strive to sign the
treaty, which is scheduled for formal ratification here in
December.
</P>
<P>
As Chretien visits Russia, there will be some signing
ceremonies. One of them is for the agreements on northern
aboriginal peoples, and another on cooperation and information
exchanges in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
After the Russia visit, the Canadian prime minister will fly to
Edinburgh, Scotland, to attend the Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting from October 24 to 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
